{"title_page": "Carteret High School", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n| name        = Carteret High School\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| motto       = \n| established = 1929\n| grades      = [[ninth grade|9]]-[[twelfth grade|12]]\n| district    = [[Carteret School District]]\n| type        = [[state school|Public]] [[Secondary education in the United States|high school]]\n| principal   = David Salvatore\n| principal_label1 = Vice principal\n| principal1  = Christina Rozanski\n| enrollment  = 1,019 (as of 2016-17)<ref name=NCES/>\n| faculty     = 82.0 [[full-time equivalent|FTEs]]<ref name=NCES/>\n| ratio       = 12.4:1<ref name=NCES/>\n| us_nces_school_id = 3402820<ref name=NCES/>\n| teamname    = Ramblers<ref name=NJSIAAprofile/>\n| conference  = [[Greater Middlesex Conference]]\n| colors      = {{Color box|RoyalBlue}} Royal blue and<br>{{Color box|White}} white<ref name=NJSIAAprofile/>\n| publication = \n| location    = 199 Washington Avenue<br>[[Carteret, New Jersey|Carteret]], [[New Jersey|NJ]] 07008\n| country     = United States\n| coordinates = {{Coord|40.580765|-74.22697|region:US_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = USA New Jersey Middlesex County#USA New Jersey#USA\n| accreditation = [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]]<ref name=MSA-CESS/>\n| information = \n| website     = {{Official website|https://chs.carteretschools.org}}\n}}\n'''Carteret High School''' is a four-year [[comprehensive high school|comprehensive]] [[state school|public]] [[Secondary education in the United States|high school]] that serves students in [[ninth grade|ninth]] through [[twelfth grade]]s from [[Carteret, New Jersey|Carteret]] in [[Middlesex County, New Jersey|Middlesex County]], [[New Jersey]], United States, as the lone secondary school of the [[Carteret School District]].  The school has been accredited by the [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]] Commission on Secondary Schools since 1929.<ref name=MSA-CESS>[http://www.msa-cess.org/default.aspx?RelID=606553 Carteret High School], [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]] Commission on Elementary and Secondary Schools. Accessed February 8, 2018.</ref>\n\nAs of the 2016\u201317 school year, the school had an enrollment of 1,019 students and 82.0 classroom teachers (on an [[full-time equivalent|FTE]] basis), for a [[student\u2013teacher ratio]] of 12.4:1. There were 614 students (60.3% of enrollment) eligible for [[National School Lunch Act|free lunch]] and 64 (6.3% of students) eligible for reduced-cost lunch.<ref name=NCES>[https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=3402820&ID=340282003268 School data for Carteret High School], [[National Center for Education Statistics]]. Accessed July 22, 2019.</ref> in 2019, 18% achieved proficiency in mathematics and 44% in reading. The graduation rate is 82%.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/new-jersey/districts/carteret-public-schools/carteret-high-school-12500</ref>\n\n[[Advanced Placement]] (AP) courses are offered in [[AP Biology]]. The Project Acceleration Program allows students to receive college credit from [[Seton Hall University]] and over 200 other colleges and universities. Schedule permitting, students may also earn college credits by attending classes at [[Middlesex County College]].<ref>[http://www.carteretschools.org/district.cfm District Information] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208161823/http://www.carteretschools.org/district.cfm |date=2012-02-08 }}, Carteret School District. Accessed November 8, 2012.</ref>\n\n==Awards, recognition and rankings==\nThe school was the 261st-ranked public high school in New Jersey out of 339 schools statewide in ''[[New Jersey Monthly]]'' magazine's September 2014 cover story on the state's \"Top Public High Schools\", using a new ranking methodology.<ref>Staff. [http://njmonthly.com/articles/towns_and_schools/top-schools-alphabetical-list.html \"Top Schools Alphabetical List 2014\"], ''[[New Jersey Monthly]]'', September 2, 2014. Accessed September 5, 2014.</ref> The school had been ranked 296th in the state of 328 schools in 2012, after being ranked 302nd in 2010 out of 322 schools listed.<ref>Staff. [http://njmonthly.com/articles/towns_and_schools/the-top-new-jersey-high-schools-alphabetical.html \"The Top New Jersey High Schools: Alphabetical\"], ''[[New Jersey Monthly]]'', August 16, 2012. Accessed August 29, 2012.</ref> The magazine ranked the school 272nd in 2008 out of 316 schools.<ref>Staff. [http://njmonthly.com/articles/towns_and_schools/highschoolrankings/top-high-schools-2010.html \"2010 Top High Schools\"], ''[[New Jersey Monthly]]'', August 16, 2010. Accessed November 2, 2011.</ref> The school was ranked 312th in the magazine's September 2010 issue, which surveyed 332 schools across the state.<ref>[http://njmonthly.com/articles/towns_and_schools/highschoolrankings/top-high-schools-2010.html \"Top New Jersey High Schools 2010: By Rank\"], ''[[New Jersey Monthly]]'', September 2008, posted August 7, 2008. Accessed August 19, 2008.</ref>  Schooldigger.com ranked the school 270th out of 367 public high schools statewide in its 2010 rankings (an increase of 17 positions from the 2009 rank) which were based on the combined percentage of students classified as proficient or above proficient on the language arts literacy and mathematics components of the  [[High School Proficiency Assessment]] (HSPA).<ref>[http://www.schooldigger.com/schoolrank.aspx?Level=3&findschool=0282003268 New Jersey High School Rankings: 11th Grade HSPA Language Arts Literacy & HSPA Math 2009-2010]{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Schooldigger.com. Accessed December 30, 2011.</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\nThe Carteret High School Ramblers<ref name=NJSIAAprofile/> compete in the [[Greater Middlesex Conference]], which includes public and private [[secondary education in the United States|high schools]] located in the greater Middlesex County area and operates under the supervision of the [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]] (NJSIAA).<ref>[https://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/2019-2020%20L%26C%20Officers-Schools_0.pdf League & Conference Officers/Affiliated Schools 2019-2020], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 22, 2019.</ref> With 770 students in grades 10\u201312, the school was classified by the NJSIAA for the 2019\u201320 school year as Group III for most athletic competition purposes, which included schools with an enrollment of 761 to 1,058 students in that grade range.<ref>[https://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/General%20Classifications%20%2719-%2720.pdf NJSIAA General Public School Classifications 2019-2020]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 22, 2019.</ref> For football, the school was classified by the NJSIAA as North Jersey Group III for 2018\u201320.<ref>[https://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/Football%20classifications%20%2718-%2720.pdf NJSIAA Football Public School Classifications 2019-2020]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 24, 2019.</ref>\n\nSchool colors are royal blue and white. Sports offered include softball, bowling (men and women), track and field spring (men and women), soccer (men and women), basketball (men and women), football, tennis (women), wrestling (men) and baseball (men).<ref name=NJSIAAprofile>[http://www.njsiaa.org/carteret-high-school Carteret High School], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed October 29, 2015.</ref>\n\nThe boys' basketball team won the Group III state championship in 1932 vs. [[Weehawken High School]] by a final score of 28-27<ref>Staff. [https://www.nytimes.com/1932/03/20/archives/trentons-quintet-wins-jersey-title-beats-south-side-of-newark-36-to.html \"Trenton's Quintet Wins Jersey Title; Beats South Side of Newark, 36 to 30, to Take Class A High School Honors. Carteret Class B Victor; Downs Woodrow Wilson of Weehawken, 28 to 27 -- Class A Prep Crown to St. Benedict's.\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 20, 1932. Accessed October 28, 2015.</ref> and the Group II title in 1934 with a 42\u201338 victory over [[Ramsey High School (New Jersey)|Ramsey High School]] in the tournament final.<ref>Staff. [https://www.nytimes.com/1934/03/18/archives/trenton-high-five-keeps-state-title-halts-union-hill-2919-to-score.html \"Trenton High Five Keeps State Title; Halts Union Hill, 29-19, to Score Third Year in Row in New Jersey Tourney.\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 18, 1934. Accessed October 28, 2015. \"Carteret conquered Ramsey, 42-28, for the Group 2 high school title.\"</ref><ref>[https://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/2019%20Basketball%20History_0.pdf NJSIAA Boys Basketball Championship History], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 25, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe boys track team won the indoor track Group III state championship in 1973 and the Group II title in 1987.<ref>[https://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/19%20Group%20Championship%20History.pdf NJSIAA Indoor Group Championship History], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 25, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe football team won the NJSIAA state sectional championships in Central Jersey Group III in 1976 and in Central Jersey Group II in 1992, 1996, 2007 and 2012.<ref>[https://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/17%20Football.pdf NJSIAA Football History], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 24, 2019.</ref> The 2007 football team won the Central Jersey, Group II state sectional championship with a 20\u201314 over [[Rumson-Fair Haven High School]] in a game played at [[Rutgers Stadium]], The win was Carteret's fourth sectional title, and its first since 1996. The 2012 football team went undefeated at 12-0 and were crowned Central Jersey Group II champions as well. They beat Weequahic by the score of 13\u201312 in a game played at Metlife Stadium.<ref>Moretti, Mike. [http://www.nj.com/starledger/stories/index.ssf?/base/sports-1/1196660450294840.xml&coll=1 \"Lewin's TD lifts Carteret past Rumson\"], ''[[The Star-Ledger]]'', December 3, 2007. Accessed December 3, 2007. \"But with senior tailback Byron Lewin picking up 143 yards on 22 carries and scoring the winning touchdown with 2:18 to go, Carteret defeated Rumson, 20-14, in the NJSIAA/Gatorade Central Jersey, Group 2 championship game before 4,000 at Rutgers Stadium in Piscataway. It was Carteret's first state title since 1996 and fourth in six final appearances.\"</ref><ref>[http://www.bracketmaker.com/tmenu.cfm?tid=246272&tclass=Central%2C%20Group%20II 2007 Football - Central, Group II], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed December 3, 2007.</ref>\n\nThe boys bowling team won the overall state championship in 2005.<ref>[https://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/19%20Bowling.pdf History of NJSIAA Boys Bowling Championships], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 25, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe girls bowling team won the Group II state championship in 2008.<ref>[https://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/19%20Bowling_0.pdf History of NJSIAA Girls Bowling Championships], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 25, 2019.</ref>\n\n== Administration ==\nCore members of the school's administration are:<ref>[https://chs.carteretschools.org/apps/staff/ Staff Directory], Carteret High School. Accessed July 26, 2019.</ref>\n*David Salvatore, Principal<ref>[https://chs.carteretschools.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=1325272&type=d&pREC_ID=1522715 Principal's Message], Carteret High School. Accessed July 26, 2019.</ref>\n*Christina Rozanski, Vice Principal\n\nThen vice principal Nicholas Sysock was suspended without pay in October 2012 after being charged with possession of child pornography.<ref>Makin, Cheryl. [http://www.mycentraljersey.com/article/20121024/NJNEWS/310240064/Carteret-High-School-Vice-Principal-Nicholas-Sysock-Rahway-arrested-child-pornography-charges-Tuesday \"Carteret High School Vice Principal Nicholas Sysock of Rahway was arrested on child pornography charges Tuesday\"], ''[[Courier News]]'', October 24, 2012. Accessed November 8, 2012. \"Shock and dismay continues to rock the community in the wake of Carteret High School Vice Principal Nicholas G. Sysock's arrest on child pornography charges.... Ahearn said that as a result of the arrest and formal charges, Sysock has been suspended without pay or benefits immediately.\"</ref> After pleading guilty to a single count of possession of child pornography, Syscock was sentenced in August 2013 to three years in prison and will have limits on his access to children after his release.<ref>Epstein, Sue. [http://www.nj.com/middlesex/index.ssf/2013/08/former_carteret_high_school_vice_principal_sentenced_to_prison_for_possession_child_pornography.html \"Former Carteret High School vice principal sentenced to prison for possessing of child porn\"], NJ ADvance Media for [[NJ.com]], August 15, 2013. Accessed October 4, 2017. \"A former vice principal at Carteret High School was sentenced today to 37 months in prison for possessing child pornography. Nicholas Sysock, 54, of Rahway, pleaded guilty earlier in the year to one count of possession of child pornography, U.S. Attorney Paul Fishman said.\"</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Jim Babjak]] (born 1957), founding member of [[The Smithereens]].<ref>Cahillane, Kevin. [https://www.nytimes.com/2004/10/10/nyregion/not-fade-away-the-smithereens-monument-to-persistence.html \"Not Fade Away: The Smithereens' Monument to Persistence\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 10, 2004. Accessed November 3, 2007. \"The band formed in 1980 when three Carteret High School graduates (class of 1975) and childhood friends (Mr. Babjak, Dennis Diken on drums and Mike Mesaros on bass) met Pat DiNizio, a Scotch Plains singer-songwriter-garbage man.\"</ref>\n* [[Joseph A. Cafasso]] (born 1956), former [[Fox News]] consultant on military and [[counterterrorism]] issues who left the network after allegations surfaced that he misrepresented his military record.<ref>Rutenberg, Jim. [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/29/business/at-fox-news-the-colonel-who-wasn-t.html \"At Fox News, the Colonel Who Wasn't\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', April 29, 2002. Accessed December 30, 2011. \"Born in 1956, he graduated from Carteret High School in Carteret, N.J., military records show.\"</ref>\n* [[Dennis Diken]] (born 1957, class of 1975), founding member of [[The Smithereens]].<ref name=Carteret1975>[http://www.ci.carteret.nj.us/controls/NewsFeed.aspx?FeedID=129 The Smithereens to perform 30th anniversary concert in Carteret] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205071928/http://www.ci.carteret.nj.us/controls/NewsFeed.aspx?FeedID=129 |date=2014-12-05 }}, Borough of Carteret, press release dated July 20, 2010. Accessed November 26, 2014. \"The Smithereens are known for writing and playing catchy 1960s-influenced power pop. Guitarist Jim Babjak , drummer Dennis Diken, and former bass player Mike Mesaros graduated Carteret High School in 1975, and formed the group with Scotch Plains singer Pat DiNizio in 1980.\"</ref>\n* [[Keith Hughes (basketball)|Keith Hughes]] (1968-2014), former professional basketball player who coached the Carteret High School basketball team for one season.<ref>Prunty, Brendan. [http://www.nj.com/rutgersbasketball/index.ssf/2014/02/former_rutgers_basketball_star_keith_hughes_passes_away_at_age_45.html \"Former Rutgers basketball star Keith Hughes passes away at age 45\"], ''[[The Star-Ledger]]'', February 10, 2014. Accessed October 4, 2017. \"In 2006, he took over as the varsity coach at his alma mater, guiding Carteret High School for one season.\"</ref>\n* [[Art McMahon]] (born 1946, class of 1964), [[defensive back]] for the [[New England Patriots|Boston / New England Patriots]] football team from 1968-1970 and 1972.<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/McMaAr20.htm Art McMahon], [[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]. Accessed January 9, 2018.</ref>\n* [[Joe Medwick]] (1911-1975), [[left fielder]] for the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] who was inducted into the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum]] in 1968.<ref>Staff. [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1975/03/22/92190360.pdf \"Ducky Medwick, Slugger For Gas House Gang, Dies\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 22, 1975. Accessed October 19, 2014. \"Medwick was born in Carteret, N. J,. on Nov. 24, 1911, and went on to star at Carteret High School in track, football, basketball, and baseball.\"</ref>\n* [[Mike Mesaros (musician)|Mike Mesaros]] (class of 1975), founding member of [[The Smithereens]].<ref name=Carteret1975/>\n* [[Laurence S. Weiss]] (c. 1919\u20132003), business executive and politician who served in the [[New Jersey Senate]] from 1978 to 1992.<ref>[[Frank Pallone|Pallone, Frank]]. [http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CREC-1994-09-29/html/CREC-1994-09-29-pt1-PgE57.htm \"Tribute To Laurence Weiss\"], ''[[Congressional Record]]'', Volume 140, Number 139 (September 29, 1994). Accessed September 24, 2015. \"Mr. Speaker, the story of Larry Weiss is one of the great American success stories. Born in Hungary, he immigrated to the United States with his parents at the age of 3. The Weiss family settled first in Jersey City, then Carteret, where Larry went through the public schools and graduated from the high school.\"</ref>\n* [[Jason Worilds]] (born 1988), outside linebacker for the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]].<ref>Vrentas, Jenny. [http://www.nj.com/sports/nfldraft/index.ssf/2010/04/steelers_draft_carteret_produc.html \"Steelers draft Carteret product Jason Worilds in second round of NFL Draft\"], ''[[The Star-Ledger]]'', April 23, 2010. Accessed July 15, 2010.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130904180217/http://carteretschools.org/CarteretHigh.cfm Carteret High School]\n*[http://www.carteretschools.org/ Carteret School District]\n*{{NJReportCard|23|0750|0|Carteret School District}}\n*[https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_list.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=3402820 Data for the Carteret School District], [[National Center for Education Statistics]]\n\n{{Middlesex County, New Jersey High Schools}}\n{{Greater Middlesex Conference}}\n\n[[Category:Carteret, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Middle States Commission on Secondary Schools]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Middlesex County, New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n| name        = Carteret High School\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| motto       = \n| established = 1929\n| grades      = [[ninth grade|9]]-[[twelfth grade|12]]\n| district    = [[Carteret School District]]\n| type        = [[state school|Public]] [[Secondary education in the United States|high school]]\n| principal   = David Salvatore\n| principal_label1 = Vice principal\n| principal1  = Christina Rozanski\n| enrollment  = 1,019 (as of 2016-17)<ref name=NCES/>\n| faculty     = 82.0 [[full-time equivalent|FTEs]]<ref name=NCES/>\n| ratio       = 12.4:1<ref name=NCES/>\n| us_nces_school_id = 3402820<ref name=NCES/>\n| teamname    = Ramblers<ref name=NJSIAAprofile/>\n| conference  = [[Greater Middlesex Conference]]\n| colors      = {{Color box|RoyalBlue}} Royal blue and<br>{{Color box|White}} white<ref name=NJSIAAprofile/>\n| publication = \n| location    = 199 Washington Avenue<br>[[Carteret, New Jersey|Carteret]], [[New Jersey|NJ]] 07008\n| country     = United States\n| coordinates = {{Coord|40.580765|-74.22697|region:US_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = USA New Jersey Middlesex County#USA New Jersey#USA\n| accreditation = [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]]<ref name=MSA-CESS/>\n| information = \n| website     = {{Official website|https://chs.carteretschools.org}}\n}}\n'''Carteret High School''' is a four-year [[comprehensive high school|comprehensive]] [[state school|public]] [[Secondary education in the United States|high school]] that serves students in [[ninth grade|ninth]] through [[twelfth grade]]s from [[Carteret, New Jersey|Carteret]] in [[Middlesex County, New Jersey|Middlesex County]], [[New Jersey]], United States, as the lone secondary school of the [[Carteret School District]].  The school has been accredited by the [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]] Commission on Secondary Schools since 1929.<ref name=MSA-CESS>[http://www.msa-cess.org/default.aspx?RelID=606553 Carteret High School], [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]] Commission on Elementary and Secondary Schools. Accessed February 8, 2018.</ref>\n\nAs of the 2016-17 school year, the school had an enrollment of 1,019 students and 82.0 classroom teachers (on an [[full-time equivalent|FTE]] basis), for a [[student\u2013teacher ratio]] of 12.4:1. There were 614 students (60.3% of enrollment) eligible for [[National School Lunch Act|free lunch]] and 64 (6.3% of students) eligible for reduced-cost lunch.<ref name=NCES>[https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=3402820&ID=340282003268 School data for Carteret High School], [[National Center for Education Statistics]]. Accessed July 22, 2019.</ref> in 2019, 18% achieved proficiency in mathematics and 44% in reading. The graduation rate is 82%.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/new-jersey/districts/carteret-public-schools/carteret-high-school-12500</ref>\n\n[[Advanced Placement]] (AP) courses are offered in [[AP Biology]]. The Project Acceleration Program allows students to receive college credit from [[Seton Hall University]] and over 200 other colleges and universities. Schedule permitting, students may also earn college credits by attending classes at [[Middlesex County College]].<ref>[http://www.carteretschools.org/district.cfm District Information] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208161823/http://www.carteretschools.org/district.cfm |date=2012-02-08 }}, Carteret School District. Accessed November 8, 2012.</ref>\n\n==Awards, recognition and rankings==\nThe school was the 261st-ranked public high school in New Jersey out of 339 schools statewide in ''[[New Jersey Monthly]]'' magazine's September 2014 cover story on the state's \"Top Public High Schools\", using a new ranking methodology.<ref>Staff. [http://njmonthly.com/articles/towns_and_schools/top-schools-alphabetical-list.html \"Top Schools Alphabetical List 2014\"], ''[[New Jersey Monthly]]'', September 2, 2014. Accessed September 5, 2014.</ref> The school had been ranked 296th in the state of 328 schools in 2012, after being ranked 302nd in 2010 out of 322 schools listed.<ref>Staff. [http://njmonthly.com/articles/towns_and_schools/the-top-new-jersey-high-schools-alphabetical.html \"The Top New Jersey High Schools: Alphabetical\"], ''[[New Jersey Monthly]]'', August 16, 2012. Accessed August 29, 2012.</ref> The magazine ranked the school 272nd in 2008 out of 316 schools.<ref>Staff. [http://njmonthly.com/articles/towns_and_schools/highschoolrankings/top-high-schools-2010.html \"2010 Top High Schools\"], ''[[New Jersey Monthly]]'', August 16, 2010. Accessed November 2, 2011.</ref> The school was ranked 312th in the magazine's September 2010 issue, which surveyed 332 schools across the state.<ref>[http://njmonthly.com/articles/towns_and_schools/highschoolrankings/top-high-schools-2010.html \"Top New Jersey High Schools 2010: By Rank\"], ''[[New Jersey Monthly]]'', September 2008, posted August 7, 2008. Accessed August 19, 2008.</ref>  Schooldigger.com ranked the school 270th out of 367 public high schools statewide in its 2010 rankings (an increase of 17 positions from the 2009 rank) which were based on the combined percentage of students classified as proficient or above proficient on the language arts literacy and mathematics components of the  [[High School Proficiency Assessment]] (HSPA).<ref>[http://www.schooldigger.com/schoolrank.aspx?Level=3&findschool=0282003268 New Jersey High School Rankings: 11th Grade HSPA Language Arts Literacy & HSPA Math 2009-2010]{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Schooldigger.com. Accessed December 30, 2011.</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\nThe Carteret High School Ramblers<ref name=NJSIAAprofile/> compete in the [[Greater Middlesex Conference]], which includes public and private [[secondary education in the United States|high schools]] located in the greater Middlesex County area and operates under the supervision of the [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]] (NJSIAA).<ref>[https://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/2019-2020%20L%26C%20Officers-Schools_0.pdf League & Conference Officers/Affiliated Schools 2019-2020], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 22, 2019.</ref> With 770 students in grades 10-12, the school was classified by the NJSIAA for the 2019-20 school year as Group III for most athletic competition purposes, which included schools with an enrollment of 761 to 1,058 students in that grade range.<ref>[https://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/General%20Classifications%20%2719-%2720.pdf NJSIAA General Public School Classifications 2019-2020]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 22, 2019.</ref> For football, the school was classified by the NJSIAA as North Jersey Group III for 2018-20.<ref>[https://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/Football%20classifications%20%2718-%2720.pdf NJSIAA Football Public School Classifications 2019-2020]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 24, 2019.</ref>\n\nSchool colors are royal blue and white. Sports offered include softball, bowling (men and women), track and field spring (men and women), soccer (men and women), basketball (men and women), football, tennis (women), wrestling (men) and baseball (men).<ref name=NJSIAAprofile>[http://www.njsiaa.org/carteret-high-school Carteret High School], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed October 29, 2015.</ref>\n\nThe boys' basketball team won the Group III state championship in 1932 vs. [[Weehawken High School]] by a final score of 28-27<ref>Staff. [https://www.nytimes.com/1932/03/20/archives/trentons-quintet-wins-jersey-title-beats-south-side-of-newark-36-to.html \"Trenton's Quintet Wins Jersey Title; Beats South Side of Newark, 36 to 30, to Take Class A High School Honors. Carteret Class B Victor; Downs Woodrow Wilson of Weehawken, 28 to 27 -- Class A Prep Crown to St. Benedict's.\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 20, 1932. Accessed October 28, 2015.</ref> and the Group II title in 1934 with a 42-38 victory over [[Ramsey High School (New Jersey)|Ramsey High School]] in the tournament final.<ref>Staff. [https://www.nytimes.com/1934/03/18/archives/trenton-high-five-keeps-state-title-halts-union-hill-2919-to-score.html \"Trenton High Five Keeps State Title; Halts Union Hill, 29-19, to Score Third Year in Row in New Jersey Tourney.\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 18, 1934. Accessed October 28, 2015. \"Carteret conquered Ramsey, 42-28, for the Group 2 high school title.\"</ref><ref>[https://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/2019%20Basketball%20History_0.pdf NJSIAA Boys Basketball Championship History], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 25, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe boys track team won the indoor track Group III state championship in 1973 and the Group II title in 1987.<ref>[https://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/19%20Group%20Championship%20History.pdf NJSIAA Indoor Group Championship History], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 25, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe football team won the NJSIAA state sectional championships in Central Jersey Group III in 1976 and in Central Jersey Group II in 1992, 1996, 2007 and 2012.<ref>[https://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/17%20Football.pdf NJSIAA Football History], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 24, 2019.</ref> The 2007 football team won the Central Jersey, Group II state sectional championship with a 20-14 over [[Rumson-Fair Haven High School]] in a game played at [[Rutgers Stadium]], The win was Carteret's fourth sectional title, and its first since 1996. The 2012 football team went undefeated at 12-0 and were crowned Central Jersey Group II champions as well. They beat Weequahic by the score of 13-12 in a game played at Metlife Stadium.<ref>Moretti, Mike. [http://www.nj.com/starledger/stories/index.ssf?/base/sports-1/1196660450294840.xml&coll=1 \"Lewin's TD lifts Carteret past Rumson\"], ''[[The Star-Ledger]]'', December 3, 2007. Accessed December 3, 2007. \"But with senior tailback Byron Lewin picking up 143 yards on 22 carries and scoring the winning touchdown with 2:18 to go, Carteret defeated Rumson, 20-14, in the NJSIAA/Gatorade Central Jersey, Group 2 championship game before 4,000 at Rutgers Stadium in Piscataway. It was Carteret's first state title since 1996 and fourth in six final appearances.\"</ref><ref>[http://www.bracketmaker.com/tmenu.cfm?tid=246272&tclass=Central%2C%20Group%20II 2007 Football - Central, Group II], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed December 3, 2007.</ref>\n\nThe boys bowling team won the overall state championship in 2005.<ref>[https://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/19%20Bowling.pdf History of NJSIAA Boys Bowling Championships], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 25, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe girls bowling team won the Group II state championship in 2008.<ref>[https://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/19%20Bowling_0.pdf History of NJSIAA Girls Bowling Championships], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 25, 2019.</ref>\n\n== Administration ==\nCore members of the school's administration are:<ref>[https://chs.carteretschools.org/apps/staff/ Staff Directory], Carteret High School. Accessed July 26, 2019.</ref>\n*David Salvatore, Principal<ref>[https://chs.carteretschools.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=1325272&type=d&pREC_ID=1522715 Principal's Message], Carteret High School. Accessed July 26, 2019.</ref>\n*Christina Rozanski, Vice Principal\n\nThen vice principal Nicholas Sysock was suspended without pay in October 2012 after being charged with possession of child pornography.<ref>Makin, Cheryl. [http://www.mycentraljersey.com/article/20121024/NJNEWS/310240064/Carteret-High-School-Vice-Principal-Nicholas-Sysock-Rahway-arrested-child-pornography-charges-Tuesday \"Carteret High School Vice Principal Nicholas Sysock of Rahway was arrested on child pornography charges Tuesday\"], ''[[Courier News]]'', October 24, 2012. Accessed November 8, 2012. \"Shock and dismay continues to rock the community in the wake of Carteret High School Vice Principal Nicholas G. Sysock's arrest on child pornography charges.... Ahearn said that as a result of the arrest and formal charges, Sysock has been suspended without pay or benefits immediately.\"</ref> After pleading guilty to a single count of possession of child pornography, Syscock was sentenced in August 2013 to three years in prison and will have limits on his access to children after his release.<ref>Epstein, Sue. [http://www.nj.com/middlesex/index.ssf/2013/08/former_carteret_high_school_vice_principal_sentenced_to_prison_for_possession_child_pornography.html \"Former Carteret High School vice principal sentenced to prison for possessing of child porn\"], NJ ADvance Media for [[NJ.com]], August 15, 2013. Accessed October 4, 2017. \"A former vice principal at Carteret High School was sentenced today to 37 months in prison for possessing child pornography. Nicholas Sysock, 54, of Rahway, pleaded guilty earlier in the year to one count of possession of child pornography, U.S. Attorney Paul Fishman said.\"</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Jim Babjak]] (born 1957), founding member of [[The Smithereens]].<ref>Cahillane, Kevin. [https://www.nytimes.com/2004/10/10/nyregion/not-fade-away-the-smithereens-monument-to-persistence.html \"Not Fade Away: The Smithereens' Monument to Persistence\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 10, 2004. Accessed November 3, 2007. \"The band formed in 1980 when three Carteret High School graduates (class of 1975) and childhood friends (Mr. Babjak, Dennis Diken on drums and Mike Mesaros on bass) met Pat DiNizio, a Scotch Plains singer-songwriter-garbage man.\"</ref>\n* [[Joseph A. Cafasso]] (born 1956), former [[Fox News]] consultant on military and [[counterterrorism]] issues who left the network after allegations surfaced that he misrepresented his military record.<ref>Rutenberg, Jim. [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/29/business/at-fox-news-the-colonel-who-wasn-t.html \"At Fox News, the Colonel Who Wasn't\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', April 29, 2002. Accessed December 30, 2011. \"Born in 1956, he graduated from Carteret High School in Carteret, N.J., military records show.\"</ref>\n* [[Dennis Diken]] (born 1957, class of 1975), founding member of [[The Smithereens]].<ref name=Carteret1975>[http://www.ci.carteret.nj.us/controls/NewsFeed.aspx?FeedID=129 The Smithereens to perform 30th anniversary concert in Carteret] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205071928/http://www.ci.carteret.nj.us/controls/NewsFeed.aspx?FeedID=129 |date=2014-12-05 }}, Borough of Carteret, press release dated July 20, 2010. Accessed November 26, 2014. \"The Smithereens are known for writing and playing catchy 1960s-influenced power pop. Guitarist Jim Babjak , drummer Dennis Diken, and former bass player Mike Mesaros graduated Carteret High School in 1975, and formed the group with Scotch Plains singer Pat DiNizio in 1980.\"</ref>\n* [[Keith Hughes (basketball)|Keith Hughes]] (1968-2014), former professional basketball player who coached the Carteret High School basketball team for one season.<ref>Prunty, Brendan. [http://www.nj.com/rutgersbasketball/index.ssf/2014/02/former_rutgers_basketball_star_keith_hughes_passes_away_at_age_45.html \"Former Rutgers basketball star Keith Hughes passes away at age 45\"], ''[[The Star-Ledger]]'', February 10, 2014. Accessed October 4, 2017. \"In 2006, he took over as the varsity coach at his alma mater, guiding Carteret High School for one season.\"</ref>\n* [[Art McMahon]] (born 1946, class of 1964), [[defensive back]] for the [[New England Patriots|Boston / New England Patriots]] football team from 1968-1970 and 1972.<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/McMaAr20.htm Art McMahon], [[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]. Accessed January 9, 2018.</ref>\n* [[Joe Medwick]] (1911-1975), [[left fielder]] for the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] who was inducted into the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum]] in 1968.<ref>Staff. [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1975/03/22/92190360.pdf \"Ducky Medwick, Slugger For Gas House Gang, Dies\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 22, 1975. Accessed October 19, 2014. \"Medwick was born in Carteret, N. J,. on Nov. 24, 1911, and went on to star at Carteret High School in track, football, basketball, and baseball.\"</ref>\n* [[Mike Mesaros (musician)|Mike Mesaros]] (class of 1975), founding member of [[The Smithereens]].<ref name=Carteret1975/>\n* [[Laurence S. Weiss]] (c. 1919\u20132003), business executive and politician who served in the [[New Jersey Senate]] from 1978 to 1992.<ref>[[Frank Pallone|Pallone, Frank]]. [http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CREC-1994-09-29/html/CREC-1994-09-29-pt1-PgE57.htm \"Tribute To Laurence Weiss\"], ''[[Congressional Record]]'', Volume 140, Number 139 (September 29, 1994). Accessed September 24, 2015. \"Mr. Speaker, the story of Larry Weiss is one of the great American success stories. Born in Hungary, he immigrated to the United States with his parents at the age of 3. The Weiss family settled first in Jersey City, then Carteret, where Larry went through the public schools and graduated from the high school.\"</ref>\n* [[Jason Worilds]] (born 1988), outside linebacker for the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]].<ref>Vrentas, Jenny. [http://www.nj.com/sports/nfldraft/index.ssf/2010/04/steelers_draft_carteret_produc.html \"Steelers draft Carteret product Jason Worilds in second round of NFL Draft\"], ''[[The Star-Ledger]]'', April 23, 2010. Accessed July 15, 2010.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130904180217/http://carteretschools.org/CarteretHigh.cfm Carteret High School]\n*[http://www.carteretschools.org/ Carteret School District]\n*{{NJReportCard|23|0750|0|Carteret School District}}\n*[https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_list.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=3402820 Data for the Carteret School District], [[National Center for Education Statistics]]\n\n{{Middlesex County, New Jersey High Schools}}\n{{Greater Middlesex Conference}}\n\n[[Category:Carteret, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Middle States Commission on Secondary Schools]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Middlesex County, New Jersey]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2016-17 \u2192 2016\u201317 (5), 10-12 \u2192 10\u201312 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carteret_High_School"}
{"title_page": "McGill School of Architecture", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name        = McGill School of Architecture\n|image       = McGill_School_of_Architecture_logo.jpg\n|image_size  = 250px\n|caption     = Macdonald-Harrington Building\n|established = {{start date and age|1896}}\n|type        = [[Public university|Public]]\n|parent      = [[McGill University Faculty of Engineering|Faculty of Engineering]]<br>[[McGill University]]\n|faculty     = 44<ref name=Faculty>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/faculty|title=Faculty and Staff, Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n|director    = Martin Bressani\n|students    = 273 (Fall 2019)<ref name=Enrollment>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/es/registration-statistics|title=Enrollment Reports|publisher=McGill University|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n|undergrad   = 163 \n|postgrad    = 90 \n|doctoral    = 20<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/phd-students|title=Current Ph.D. students|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n|city        = [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]], [[Montreal]]\n|province    = [[Quebec]]\n|country     = [[Canada]]\n|coordinates = {{coord |45.5053|-73.5758|type:edu_region:CA-QC|display=inline,title}}\n|campus      = [[urban area|Urban]] \n|free_label  = Student Life\n|free        = [[Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture#Student life|ASA]], [[Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture#Student life|AIAS]], [[Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture#Student life|GASA]]\n|website     = {{url|https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''McGill School of Architecture''' (also known as the '''Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture''') is a constituent of the [[McGill University Faculty of Engineering|Faculty of Engineering]] at [[McGill University]] in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]]. Founded in 1896 by [[William Christopher Macdonald|Sir William Macdonald]], it is among the oldest [[architecture schools]] in [[North America]].<ref name=History>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history|title=History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref> The School offers accredited professional and post-professional programs ranging from undergraduate to PhD levels,<ref name=Programs>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/programs|title=Programs|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref> with the smallest entering class of any accredited architecture school in Canada.<ref name=Stats>{{cite web|url=https://www.acsa-arch.org/resources/data-resources/vital-statistics-on-canadian-schools-of-architecture/|title=Vital Statistics on Canadian Schools of Architecture|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> Since its founding, the School has established an international reputation and a record of producing leading professionals and researchers who have helped shape the field of architecture, including [[Moshe Safdie]], [[Arthur Erickson]], [[Raymond Moriyama]] and the founders of [[Arcop]].{{NoteTag|The founders of Arcop include [[Ray Affleck]], Guy Desbarats, Jean Michaud, [[:fr:Fred Lebensold|Fred Lebensold]], [[Hazen Sise]] and [[Dimitri Dimakopoulos]], all graduates and/or professors at the School of Architecture at some point.<ref name=Arcop>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/archives/379565/affleck-desbarats-dimakopoulos-lebensold-sise-fonds|title=Affleck, Desbarats, Dimakopoulos, Lebensold, Sise fonds|publisher=Canadian Centre for Architecture|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>}}<ref name=Alumni>{{cite web| url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews|title=Alumni Interviews|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe School of Architecture is housed in the [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]], designed by [[Andrew Taylor (architect)|Sir Andrew Taylor]], on the McGill University downtown campus. The [[McGill University Faculty of Engineering#School of Urban Planning|School of Urban Planning]] occupies the fourth floor.<ref name=CAC>{{cite web|url=http://cac.mcgill.ca/campus/buildings/Macdonald-Harrington.html|title=Macdonald-Harrington Building (formerly Macdonald Chemistry Building)|publisher=Canadian Architecture Collection, McGill Archives|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> The School also operates many auxiliary facilities, including workshops, laser cutting and 3D-printing facilities, research labs and various libraries and collections both within the Macdonald-Harrington Building and elsewhere on McGill's campus. The School is accredited by the [[Professional requirements for architects#Canada|Canadian Architectural Certification Board]] (CACB) and is recognized in the United States by the [[National Council of Architectural Registration Boards]] (NCARB).<ref name=Accreditation>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/programs/accreditation|title=Accreditation|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture, McGill University|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn September 26, 2017, the School was renamed the Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture following a [[Canadian dollar|C]]$12&nbsp;million gift from architect and McGill graduate Peter Fu.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.architectmagazine.com/design/chinese-architect-peter-guo-hua-fu-donated-12-million-to-the-mcgill-school-of-architecture_o| title=Chinese Architect Peter Guo-hua Fu Donated $12 Million to the McGill School of Architecture | publisher=Architect Magazine |author=Ayda Ayoubi| year=2017 |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nMcGill's School of Architecture, founded in 1896, is one of the oldest architecture schools in North America and the second to be established in Canada.<!-- University of Toronto had the first architecture program in Canada (1890)--><ref name=History /> It began as a [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]] style school based in the [[Arts and Crafts movement]], and became a [[Bauhaus]]-based institution under new directorship after [[World War&nbsp;II]]. The School was the first in Canada to offer a graduate planning program and a Ph.D. in Architecture.<ref name=CanadianArchitect>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/glaciermedia/docs/canadian_architect_october_2014|title=State of the Schools - Canadian Architect October Issue 2014|page=18|publisher=Canadian Architect|date=October 2014|author=Annmarie Adams|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Early history===\nIn 1890, the [[Ordre des architectes du Qu\u00e9bec|Province of Quebec Association of Architects]] adopted a constitution requiring compulsory examination for people in Quebec who wished to become professional architects. This created a need for more systematic architectural education, and the absence of such opportunities caused many aspiring Canadian architects to study in the United States, where ten architecture schools had already been established.<ref name=History /> Canada did not yet have any formal architectural education, and the only forms of architectural education in Montreal were periodical lectures by local practising architects at McGill's affiliated religious colleges. This new need for architectural education is an important factor that led to the founding of the School of Architecture at McGill University.\n[[File:William Christopher Macdonald.jpg|thumb|upright|[[William Christopher Macdonald|Sir William C. Macdonald]], 4th [[List of McGill University people#List of chancellors|Chancellor of McGill University]], created a Chair in Architecture at McGill in 1896.]]\n\nIn 1896, [[William Christopher Macdonald|Sir William C. Macdonald]] created a chair in architecture at McGill which was led by [[Stewart Henbest Capper]]. At this time, the School offered a four-year course to prepare students for professional accreditation. The first graduating class was composed of three students: George Taylor Hyde, Norman M. McLeod and Frank Peder. Professor Capper gave all lectures in architecture, and Henry F. Armstrong, the only other full-time professor, taught art classes and modelling.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/beginning|title=The beginning with Stewart H. Capper, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe second director of the School, [[Percy Nobbs]], arrived at McGill in 1903 to only two students: Gordon H. Blackader and H.&nbsp;E. Shorey. He divided the four-year course into two streams, the BArch degree and the BSc degree in Architectural Engineering. Three new staff were hired in 1906, and three years later, [[Philip J. Turner]] joined the faculty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/nobbs|title=Legacy of Nobbs, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1913, [[Ramsay Traquair (architect)|Ramsay Traquair]] became the new director of the School. He designed the Baillie library window and the flag above the [[McCall MacBain Arts Building|Arts Building]] at McGill, which still remain today.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/traquair|title= Legacy of Traquair, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/McGillLibrary-cac_finding-aid_ramsay-traquair-book1-guide-18112/page/n21/mode/2up|title=Ramsay Traquair and his successors : guide to the Archive|date=1987|publisher=Blackader-Lauterman Library of Architecture and Art, McGill University|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>{{page needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:Arts Building, McGill University.jpg|thumb|upright|The McGill flag, designed by [[Ramsay Traquair (architect)|Ramsay Traquair]] and presented to McGill in 1921, flown above the [[McCall MacBain Arts Building|Arts Building]].]]\n\nIn 1921, the School had its first \"sketching school\" in [[Quebec City]], a tradition that has been carried on annually to various destinations since as a credited course. [[Arthur Lismer]], a founding member of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]], taught this course at the School for over a decade starting in 1941.<ref name=Lismer>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/library/channels/event/exhibition-arthur-lismers-mcgill-sketchbook-240235|title=Exhibition: Arthur Lismer\u2019s McGill Sketchbook|publisher=McGill Library|year=2015|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 1939, Turner succeeded Traquair, who had completed a 26-year tenure as director of the School. At this time, the principal of McGill, [[Lewis Williams Douglas]], considered phasing out architectural education at the university due to low enrollment; however he faced a great deal of backlash from Turner and several famous architects from Montreal, and eventually abandoned the idea. Among these architects was [[Ernest Cormier]], who taught at the School from 1919 to 1920.<ref name=Cormier>{{cite web|url=https://www.pc.gc.ca/en/culture/clmhc-hsmbc/res/doc/information-backgrounder/Ernest_Cormier|title=Ernest Cormier (1885-1980)|publisher=Parks Canada|accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nUnder Turner's tenure, the door to co-ed education was opened, and in 1943 [[Catherine Mary Wisnicki]] became the School's first female graduate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/turner|title=Legacy of Turner, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> Wisnicki would also become the fourth female member of the [[Ontario Association of Architects]], which was founded in 1889.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Ontario Association of Architects|journal=Canadian Architect and Builder|date=April 1889|volume=2|issue=4|page=40|url=https://archive.org/stream/canadianarchitec01onta#page/n29/mode/1up|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Mid-century===\nFollowing the retirement of Turner as director of the School of Architecture, [[John Bland (architect)|John Bland]] became director in 1941. In 1945, a new five-year program was adopted for the next two decades. After the [[World War Two|war]], the School of Architecture increased its staff and doubled its physical accommodation due to the surge in university enrollment. This required the School to briefly use McGill's [[Dawson College]], a [[satellite campus]] in St. Jean, Quebec, to accommodate its students. By 1947, the School had become so cramped that a former Victorian residential building on University Street was vacated to make room for the School's students.<ref name=McGillForties />\n\nAround this time, Professor Frederic Lasserre of McGill's School of Architecture left the university to establish a new School of Architecture at the [[University of British Columbia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sala.ubc.ca/about/history|title=History|publisher=University of British Columbia School of Architecture + Landscape Architecture|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> and invited McGill Architecture graduates [[Catherine Mary Wisnicki]], [[Peter Oberlander]] and [[Arthur Erickson]] to teach at his new school. \n\nIn 1946, [[Harold Spence-Sales]] was appointed Associate Professor of Design. He and Bland established the first post-graduate architecture and planning program in Canada. Enrollment had grown from 23 students in 1941 to 133 full-time students in the 1949/1950 academic year.<ref name=McGillForties>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/forties|title=The School with John Bland:1940s, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> Beginning in this academic year, the professional program was extended to six years, with first-year students following the engineering curriculum.\n\nDuring the early 1950s, three new teachers were added to the faculty, including Hazen Sise and Guy Desbarats who would later found [[Arcop]] with Fred Lebensold, [[Ray Affleck]], and [[Dimitri Dimakopoulos]]&nbsp;\u2013 all former students or teachers of the School.<ref name=Arcop />\n\nEnrollment was steady during the 1950s due to the limitations of physical space, but a four-story expansion of the McConnell Building in the 1960s allowed for growth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/fifties|title=The School with John Bland:1950s, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1961, [[Moshe Safdie]] published his master's thesis which became the basis for [[Habitat 67]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} That year, McGill Professor Douglas Shadbolt left the School to found the first architecture program at the Nova Scotia Technical College (later known as [[Technical University of Nova Scotia|Technical University of Nova Scotia]] [TUNS]) in [[Halifax, Canada|Halifax]], and 8 years later founded the School of Architecture (later the Azrieli School of Architecture and Urbanism) at [[Carleton University]] in [[Ottawa, Ontario|Ottawa]].<ref name=Shadbolt>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/douglas-shadbolt|title=Douglas Shadbolt|publisher=The Canadian Encyclopedia|author=Michael McMordie|date=16 December 2013|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, [[John C. Parkin]], [[Harry Mayerovitch]] and Victor Prus, all distinguished practicing architects, joined the faculty as visiting professors. In the following years, [[Ray Affleck]], Fred Lebensold, [[Eva Vecsei|Andre Vecsei]], [[Warren Chalk]] and <!--Moshe--> Safdie also became visiting professors.<ref name=McGillSixties />\n\nIn the late 1960s, the six-year architecture program became a four-year program with the introduction of [[CEGEP]]s in Quebec.<ref name=McGillSixties>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/sixties|title=The School with John Bland:1960s, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===1970\u2013present===\nIn 1970, Spence-Sales retired from the faculty. Later that year, the graduate planning program was reorganized by Professor David Farley, which resulted in the establishment of the independent School of Urban Planning on the fourth floor of the [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]]. Over the next decade and a half, the School changed directorship three times, with Professor Norbert Schoenauer heading the School from 1972 until 1975, Professor Derek Drummond from 1975 until 1985 and Professor Bruce Anderson in 1985.<ref name=Highlights /> \n\nIn 1987, the School moved from the Engineering building to the Macdonald-Harrington Building. Macdonald-Harrington was initially named the Macdonald Chemistry Building but was renamed after Bernard Harrington, the building's first chemistry professor. The building is one of the many donations made by [[William Christopher Macdonald|Sir William Macdonald]] and was designed by Sir Andrew Taylor to accommodate the Departments of Chemistry and Mining in 1896. The building was renovated for architecture and urban planning students by architects [[Arcop]] in 1987.<ref name=CAC />\n\nIn 1989, the PhD in Architecture was introduced as an ''ad hoc'' program. In 1990, Derek Drummond returned for another six years as the School's director, replaced by Professor David Covo in 1996. In 1997, the PhD program was officially approved by the Minister of Education as the first in Canada,<ref name=CanadianArchitect /> and the School had its first PhD graduate, Lily Chi. In 1999, the professional BArch degree was replaced by the new MArchI professional degree, leaving the undergraduate BSc in architecture. Two years later, the School graduated its first class in the MArchI program.<ref name=Highlights /> \n\nIn 2003, philanthropist [[David Azrieli]] endowed an annual lecture at the School, called the [[McGill School of Architecture#Lecture Series|David J. Azrieli Lecture Series]], which has attracted many celebrity [[starchitect|starchitects]] to the School, including seven [[Pritzker Prize]] laureates. \n\nAfter an 11-year tenure as director, Covo stepped down and Professor [[Michael Jemtrud]] became director of the School in 2007. The next year, Jemtrud founded the Facility for Architectural Research in Media and Mediation (FARMM) at the School of Architecture with more than $1&nbsp;million in funding from the [[Canada Foundation for Innovation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ca.linkedin.com/company/facility-for-architectural-research-in-media-and-mediation-farmm-|title=Facility for Architectural Research in Media and Mediation (FARMM)|website=LinkedIn|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> FARMM produced many award-winning projects and serves as the research hub for the School.<ref name=FARMM>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/farmm|title=Facility for Architectural Research in Media Mediation|publisher=McGill University|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Professor [[Annmarie Adams]] became the first female director of the School of Architecture. Since 2015, the director has been Professor Martin Bressani.<ref name=Highlights>{{cite web| url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school|title=Highlights of the School's History|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Directors===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Director !! Tenure<ref name=Highlights />\n|-\n| [[Stewart Henbest Capper]] || 1896\u20131903 \n|-\n| [[Percy Nobbs]] || 1903\u20131913\n|-\n| [[Ramsay Traquair (architect)|Ramsay Traquair]] || 1913\u20131939\n|-\n| [[Philip J. Turner]] || 1939\u20131941\n|-\n| [[John Bland (architect)|John Bland]] || 1941\u20131972\n|-\n| Norbert Schoenauer || 1972\u20131975\n|-\n| Derek Drummond || 1975\u20131985\n|-\n| Bruce Anderson || 1985\u20131990\n|-\n| Derek Drummond || 1990\u20131996\n|-\n| David Covo || 1996\u20132007\n|-\n| [[Michael Jemtrud]] || 2007\u20132011\n|-\n| [[Annmarie Adams]] || 2011\u20132015\n|-\n|Martin Bressani\n|2015\u2013present\n|}\n\n==Buildings and resources==\n===Macdonald-Harrington Building===\n[[File:McGill University Building3.jpg|thumb|upright|The [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]], home to the McGill School of Architecture since 1987.]]\nThe [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]] is the home of the Peter Guo-hua School of Architecture, and also contains the [[McGill University Faculty of Engineering#School of Urban Planning|School of Urban Planning]] on the fourth level.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/engineering/faculty-staff/facilities/buildings/macdonald-harrington|title=Macdonald-Harrington Building|publisher=McGill Faculty of Engineering|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> As architecture students progress through the years of the undergraduate program, they move through the design studios as well, with each year's respective studio located on a different level of the Macdonald-Harrington Building. The Master's studios are located on the top level, while the PhD studios are located on the same level as the U1 studios and the School's administration. The ground level, which can be accessed from the Frank Dawson Adams (FDA) building,<ref name=Map>{{cite web|url=https://maps.mcgill.ca/?lat=45.50559139299993&lng=-73.57612234168278&z=16.000000&id=MacdonaldHarr|title=McGill University Interactive Campus Map|publisher=McGill Campus Maps|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> contains the lecture hall known as \"G-10\", one of the only lecture rooms in Macdonald-Harrington that is not exclusive to architecture or urban planning students. G-10 also hosts [[McGill School of Architecture#Lecture series|the School's lecture series]].<ref name=LectureSeries>{{cite web| url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/news-events/lectures|title=Lecture Series|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n \nThe ground floor also contains the ASA Supply Store where students can purchase drafting kits,<ref name=SupplyStore>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/asa.supplystore/|title=ASA Supply Store|publisher=Architecture Students' Association|website=Facebook|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> as well as the architecture student lounge, known as the \"Cellar\", which unlike most lounges at McGill, is accessible 24/7 to architecture students.<ref name=Cellar>{{cite web|url=https://eus.wiki/Departmental_Lounges|title=Departmental Lounges|website=EUS (Engineering Undergraduate Society) Wiki|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> The first floor, above the ground level, contains the U2 studio as well as three crit rooms, the largest among them dubbed the \"exhibition room\" due to its common hosting of exhibitions of students' and outside guests' work. The U3 studios, used by students in their final year of undergraduate studies, are located on the third floor of Macdonald-Harrington.\n\nAll of the model-making resources students need are located within the architecture building, and apart from materials and printing, which must be purchased, all resources can be used free-of-charge and are exclusive to architecture students.\n\n====Workshop====\nThe workshop is located in the basement and ground floor of the Macdonald-Harrington building, and provides students with all of their model-making needs. The workshop contains various equipment and power tools for working with wood, plaster, glass, acrylics and metal, and also contains other facilities, including a fumehood for sandblasting, spray painting, casting and mould-making.\n\nWorkshop facilities include a Laser Cutting Room with three Universal Laser Cutter machines that students can use free-of-charge to cut and engrave acrylic, MDF, wood, styrene and other sheet materials. The workshop also includes 3D-printing machines, two of which are located inside the U3 studios on the third floor. <ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/workshop|title=Workshop facilities|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nMcGill University as a whole has a 3D-printing hub called \"the Cube\" which offers 3D-printing services to McGill students.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://uprint3d.xyz/|title=The Cube, McGill University|accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Media Centre====\nThe Media Centre is located in the Macdonald-Harrington building and is available exclusively to architecture students, faculty and staff at McGill.  \nThe Centre includes a traditional dark room for developing film photographs, a photography studio/light room for students to photograph their work as well as a printing room with multiple large format printers and scanners. The Media Centre also lends out digital cameras, lenses, tripods and light tents to students.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/media-centre|title=Media Centre|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref><!--cleaned up the copyright issues-->\n\n====FARMM====\nThe Facility for Architectural Research in Media and Mediation (FARMM) is the research hub of the McGill School of Architecture, located on the first floor of the Macdonald-Harrington Building. Founded in 2008 by the director of the School at the time, [[Michael Jemtrud]], with over $1&nbsp;million in funding from the [[Canada Foundation for Innovation]], FARMM's mandate is to explore collaborative design utilizing advanced technologies in computation and networking. The facility links researchers and students from the School of Architecture to other researchers around the world, and contains state-of-the-art networking, simulation and imaging, and fabrication infrastructure.<ref name=FARMM />\n\n===Libraries and collections===\n====John Bland Canadian Architecture Collection====\nThe [[Canadian Architecture Collection]] (CAC) is one of the [[McGill University Library|McGill Libraries]]' Special Collections. Students and professors at these schools are required to document their work and entrust it with the Canadian Architecture Collection for safe-keeping. \n\nThe Collection currently consists of over 150,000 drawings, 25,000 photographs and 11,000 slides, 190 models, 300 maps and 400 metres of papers of nineteenth- and twentieth-century architects in Canada.<ref name=JBCAC>{{cite web| url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/collection|title=John Bland Canadian Architecture Collection|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref> The largest fond of major Canadian architects is that of [[Moshe Safdie]], who donated his archives to the collection with an ongoing bequest since 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cac.mcgill.ca/moshesafdie/history.html|title=The Moshe Safdie Archive|publisher=McGill Library|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> The CAC also includes 770 papers from the course \"History of Architecture in Canada\".<ref name=JBCAC />\n\n====Architecture Slide Library====\nThe Architecture Slide Library contains more than 40,000 images, of which nineteenth- and twentieth-century images are the most heavily used. They are stored in Room 310 of the Macdonald-Harrington building, while slides from earlier periods are stored in the Media Centre.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/slides|title=Architecture Slide Library|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Orson Wheeler Architectural Model Collection====\nThe Orson Wheeler Architectural Model Collection contains over two hundred scale  architectural models of structures from around the world. The models were created between 1940 and 1990 by Orson Wheeler, a sculptor and former professor at McGill's School of Architecture.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/model|title=Orson Wheeler Architectural Model Collection|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nA small collection of his works are on display in the front vestibule of the Macdonald-Harrington building.\n\n====Blackader-Lauterman Library of Architecture and Art====\nThe Blackader-Lauterman Library of Architecture and Art is the University's parent library for the Schools of Architecture and Urban Planning, and is located on the upper floor of the Humanities and Social Sciences Library, one of thirteen branches of the McGill Library.\n\nThe library was established through a donation from the family of the late Gordon H. Blackader, one of the first students to study at the School of Architecture whose life was cut short during World War&nbsp;I. The library was renamed the Blackader-Lauterman Library of Architecture and Art during the 1940s after the family of sculptor [[Dinah Lauterman]] donated in her memory. \n\nThe library contains over 79,000 monographs and journal subscriptions, and has a substantial collection of over 3000 rare books from 1511 to 2009 housed in the [[Rare Books and Special Collections Library]] at McGill. This includes a fine collection of original works by [[G.&nbsp;B. Piranesi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/library|title=Blackader-Lauterman Library of Architecture and Art|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Centre Canadien Architecture Montreal.JPG|thumb|220px|right|[[Canadian Centre for Architecture]], view of Shaughnessy House.]]\n====Canadian Centre for Architecture====\nStudents are always welcome to visit the [[Canadian Centre for Architecture|Canadian Centre for Architecture (CCA)]], which houses one of the largest architectural design collections in the world,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/canadian-heritage/news/2019/02/the-government-of-canada-supports-the-canadian-centre-for-architecture.html|title=The Government of Canada supports the Canadian Centre for Architecture|publisher=Government of Canada|date=11 February 2019|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> just a 20-minute walk away from the downtown campus. The CCA collaborates regularly with the McGill School of Architecture, and organized the 2019 CCA Interuniversity [[Charrette]] with the School, which took place over a week in November and involved more than 10 universities in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.qc.ca/charrette/2019/en/index.html|title=About, CCA Interuniversity Charette|publisher=Canadian Centre for Architecture|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n===Architecture Students' Association (ASA)===\nThe Architecture Students' Association (ASA) is a non-profit student-run society within the School of Architecture. The society represents all undergraduate students in the School of Architecture, organizes student activities and affairs and acts as a voice for students in issues at McGill.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://mcgill.ca/engineering/students/undergraduate/student-life/student-groups-associations|title=Student Groups & Associations, Faculty of Engineering|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> The ASA is chaired by the President and run by an Executive Council composed of six Vice-President portfolios: Academic, Internal, External, Administration, Finance and Student Life. A student representative from each undergraduate year is also elected to sit on the Council. \n\nPart of the ASA's mandate is to maintain the ASA Supply Store where students can purchase drafting kits as well as the architecture lounge, also known as the \"Cellar\".<ref name=Cellar />\n\n===Graduate Architecture Students' Association (GASA)===\nThe McGill Graduate Architecture Students' Association (GASA) is a student-run society representing all graduate students at the School of Architecture. GASA is known to hold \"Late Night\" events on Thursdays, popular among students from all programs in the School.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.mcgill.ca/engage/overview/faculty-and-school-associations/graduate-faculty-and-school-associations|title=Graduate Faculty and School Associations, Engage McGill|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===American Institute of Architecture Students (AIAS)===\nAs of 2019, the School of Architecture has established a chapter of the [[American Institute of Architecture Students]], an international, non-profit, student-run organization dedicated to providing progressive programs, information and resources on critical issues to architecture students.<ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.aias.org/chapter/mcgill-university/|title=McGill University, Northeast Quad|publisher=American Institute of Architecture Students/accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Exchange and Study Abroad===\nThe Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture has close ties to several architecture schools across the world and has formal bilateral exchange agreements on a departmental level with seven schools in particular, including [[The Royal Danish Academy of Fine Arts]] in [[Copenhagen]], [[Politecnico di Milano]] in [[Milan]], [[Tongji University]] in [[Shanghai]], [[\u00c9cole Nationale Sup\u00e9rieure d'Architecture de Paris-Belleville]], [[:fr:\u00c9cole nationale sup\u00e9rieure d'architecture de Grenoble|\u00c9cole nationale sup\u00e9rieure d'architecture de Grenoble]], [[Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain]] in [[Brussels]] and [[TU Wien]] in [[Vienna]]. These bilateral agreements make it easy for undergraduate architecture students at McGill to go on exchange.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/files/architecture/bscarch_programadvisingandcourseregistration-fall_2018.pdf|title=B.Sc.(Arch.) program and Architecture Exchange Students (New and Returning Students) - STUDENT EXCHANGES|page=5|publisher=McGill University|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nStudents also have the opportunity to spend an exchange semester abroad at any of McGill University's 160+ partner institutions<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/mcgillabroad/mcgill-students-going-abroad/global-learning-opportunities|title=McGill students going abroad|publisher=McGill Abroad, McGill University|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> as long as they offer architecture exchanges, however these are more difficult to coordinate due to the competitive nature of University-wide exchanges. In addition to the seven schools with whom the School of Architecture has bilateral agreements, architecture students have spent exchange semesters at some of the top architecture schools in the world, including [[The Bartlett]] at [[University College London (UCL)]], [[National University of Singapore]], [[University of Leeds]], [[University of Liverpool]], [[University of Sheffield]] and [[Australian National University]].\n\n==Academics==\nThe School of Architecture offers a professional program in Architecture comprising a Bachelor of Science in Architecture (BSc[Arch]) and professional Master of Architecture (MArch) degree, as well as post-professional graduate programs leading to a Doctor of Philosophy (PhD) and post-professional Master of Architecture (MArch) degree. The School has a reputation for excellence in teaching, with all of its professors being either practicing architects or holding professional degrees and/or PhDs,<ref name=Faculty /> and architecture professors often being awarded teaching awards proportionately more often than other departments within the Faculty of Engineering relative to their respective sizes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/engineering/faculty-staff/teaching-research-and-service-awards|title=Teaching, Research & Service Awards, Faculty of Engineering|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Professional programs===\n* '''BSc(Arch)''' \u2013 3 years, 100 credits\n* '''MArch (Professional)''':\n** Design Studio \u2013 1.5 years, 45 credits, or\n** Design Studio (Directed Research) \u2013 2 years, 60 credits\n\nThe MArch (Professional) degree is accredited by the [[Professional requirements for architects#Canada|Canadian Architectural Certification Board]] (CACB), and is recognized by the [[National Council of Architectural Registration Boards]] (NCARB) in the United States.<ref name=Accreditation />\n\n===Post-professional research programs===\n* '''MArch (Non-Thesis)''':\n** Architectural History and Theory \u2013 45 credits\n** Urban Design and Housing \u2013 45 credits\n* '''PhD'''\n<ref name=Programs />\n\n===Admissions===\nThe McGill School of Architecture has the smallest entering class per degree offered of any architecture school in Canada. With a maximum capacity of 50 undergraduate students in the first year undergraduate studio (BSc[Arch]) and 35 students in both of the Master's (MArch&nbsp;1 and MArch&nbsp;II) studios, the School has one of the most selective and competitive sets of program offerings in the country with one of the lowest overall application-to-acceptance ratios.<ref name=Stats /> \n\nGenerally, about 5\u201310 students from outside Quebec who plan to study architecture for their undergraduate degree will spend their first year at McGill in U0, taking the necessary engineering prerequisites required for the 3-year BSc (Architecture) program at the School of Architecture. Students coming from Quebec [[CEGEP]]s enter directly into the BSc Architecture program, or U1, but are required to have received a [[Diploma of college studies|DEC]] in either pure and applied science or health sciences, as these degrees fulfill the engineering prerequisites for the Architecture program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/programs/professional#application|title=Application procedures|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture, McGill University|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOffers of acceptance into the program are based on a unique review process including an evaluation of a portfolio of works and extracurricular involvement, in addition to grades. In the 2010\u20132011 academic year, there were 687 applications with portfolios to the undergraduate BSc Architecture program with only 51 spaces, giving an overall applications to enrolments ratio of 7.42%.<ref name=Admissions>{{cite web| url=https://info.publicintelligence.net/McGillSoA-AUR.pdf| title=McGill School of Architecture: 2011 Cyclical Academic Unit Review, p.13 Section 2.0: Academic Programs, Teaching and Learning | year=2011 |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref> With the exception of the new Bioengineering degree at McGill, for Quebec [[CEGEP]] students, admissions to the School of Architecture represent the highest average [[R score]] of students accepted into the Faculty of Engineering<ref>{{cite web| url=https://info.publicintelligence.net/McGillSoA-AUR.pdf| title=McGill School of Architecture: 2011 Cyclical Academic Unit Review, p.39 Section 2.7.1 Admissions | year=2011 |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref> however in contrast to the high average R score, the lowest score admitted can sometimes be closer to the engineering average due to the importance of the portfolio in the admissions process.\n\nThe School of Architecture has one of the highest percentages of female representation at McGill, with an overall ratio of female-to-male students of approximately 2:1. As of fall&nbsp;2019, there were 119 female and 44 male undergraduate students, and 54 female and 36 male graduate students enrolled at the School. In some studios, the ratio can be as high as 8:1, such as is the case for the undergraduate class of 2021.<ref name=Enrollment />\n\n==Lecture series==\nEach year, the School of Architecture presents public lectures, exhibitions and symposia showcasing leading architects and important figures in the field. These lectures are organized by various individuals and organizations affiliated with the School. Lecture Series include lunchtime \"Brown Bag\" lectures organized by the McGill Architecture Students' Association, evening lectures sponsored by local Montreal firms such as Provencher Roy & [[NEUF Architect(e)s]],<ref name=LectureSeries /> and most notably, the annual [[David Azrieli|David J. Azrieli]] Lecture in Architecture which has brought in [[starchitect|starchitects]] from all over the world since 2003,<ref name=AzrieliLecture>{{cite web|url=https://mcgill.ca/architecture/news-events/lectures/azrieli|title=David J. Azrieli Lecture in Architecture|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture, McGill University|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> including seven [[Pritzker Prize]] laureates.{{NoteTag|Lecturers at McGill who have won the [[Pritzker Prize]] include [[Carme Pigem]], [[David Adjaye]], [[Thom Mayne]], [[Shigeru Ban]], [[Paulo Mendes da Rocha]], [[Glenn Murcutt]] and [[Jacques Herzog]].<ref name=Pritzker>{{cite web|url=https://www.pritzkerprize.com/laureates|title=Laureates|publisher=The Hyatt Foundation|website=The Pritzker Architecture Prize|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>}}<ref name=Pritzker />\n\nNotable lecturers:<ref name=LectureSeries /><ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n*[[Douglas Cardinal]] (2019\u20132020)\n*[[Carme Pigem]] (2018\u20132019) \n*[[Odile Decq]] (2018\u20132019) \n*[[Shim-Sutcliffe Architects|Brigitte Shim & Howard Sutcliffe]] (2017\u20132018)\n*[[David Adjaye]] (2016\u20132017) \n*[[Caruso St John|Adam Caruso]] (2015\u20132016) \n*[[Bruce Kuwabara]] (2014\u20132015)\n*[[Bjarke Ingels]] (2013\u20132014)\n*[[J\u00fcrgen Mayer]] (2012\u20132013)\n*[[Thom Mayne]] (2011\u20132012)\n*[[Shigeru Ban]] (2010\u20132011)\n*[[Peter Eisenman]] (2009\u20132010)\n*[[Morphosis Architects|Michael Rotondi]] (2008\u20132009)\n*[[Moshe Safdie]] (2007\u20132008)\n*[[Reiser + Umemoto|Nanako Umemoto]] (2007\u20132008)\n*[[Paulo Mendes da Rocha]] (2006\u20132007) \n*[[Glenn Murcutt]] (2005\u20132006) \n*[[Daniel Libeskind]] (2004\u20132005)\n*[[Diamond Schmitt Architects|Jack Diamond]] (2004\u20132005)\n*[[Will Alsop]] (2002\u20132003, 2004\u20132005) \n*[[Steven Holl]] (2003\u20132004)\n*[[Jacques Herzog]] (2002\u20132003) \n\n==Notable alumni and faculty==\n[[File:Raymond Moriyama.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Raymond Moriyama]], renowned architect of the [[Canadian War Museum]] and [[Scarborough Civic Centre]], graduated from McGill's MArch program in 1957.]]\n[[File:Arthur Erickson Portrait, 1984.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Arthur Erickson]], architect of the [[Museum of Glass]] and [[Roy Thompson Hall]], received his BArch degree from McGill in 1950.]]\n[[File:Moshe Safdie.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Moshe Safdie]], architect of [[Marina Bay Sands]] and [[Habitat 67]], which was originally conceived in his Master's thesis at McGill in 1961.]]\n[[File:Arthur Lismer.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Arthur Lismer]], a member of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]], taught History of Art and Theory of Design, Freehand Drawing and Sketching School at the School of Architecture.]]\n[[File:Ernest Cormier.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Ernest Cormier]], renowned Art Deco architect, taught from 1919 to 1920.]]\n===Alumni===\n*[[Caruso St John|Adam Caruso]] (BArch 1986) &ndash; co-founder of [[Caruso St John]], [[Stirling Prize]] winner\n*[[Alina Payne]] (BArch 1977) &ndash; professor of History of Art and Architecture at [[Harvard University]]\n*[[Amale Andraos]] (BArch 1996) &ndash; founder of New York-based architecture firm WORKac\n*Andre Vecsei (MArch 1973) &ndash; co-founder of Vecsei Architects with wife [[Eva Vecsei]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bluebeard.micro.org/about-the-author/|title=A cultured man who cheated death in Hungary|author=Alan Hustak|publisher=Montreal Gazette|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Anne Cormier (BArch 1982) &ndash; co-founder of Atelier Big City, 1998 [[Prix de Rome (Canada)|Prix de Rome]] winner<ref name=AtelierBigCity>{{cite web|url=https://www.atelierbigcity.com/team|title=Atelier Big City / Cormier, Cohen, Davies, architects|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Annie Lebel (BSc[Arch] 1989, BArch 1991) &ndash; co-founder of Atelier In Situ, 2001 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=Alumni2 />\n*[[Arthur Erickson]] (BArch 1950) &ndash; architect of [[Robson Square]], the [[Embassy of Canada in Washington, D.C.|Canadian Embassy]] and [[Roy Thompson Hall]]\n*[[Blanche Lemco van Ginkel|Blanche van Ginkel]] (BArch 1945) &ndash; first woman to head a faculty of architecture in Canada and be awarded a fellowship by the [[Royal Architectural Institute of Canada|RAIC]]<ref>Annmarie Adams, (2015). [http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/blanche-lemco-van-ginkel/ Article: Blanche Lemco van Ginkel], Canadian Encyclopedia. Accessed April 14, 2019.</ref>\n*[[Catherine Mary Wisnicki|Catherine Chard Wisnicki]] (B. Arch. 1943) &ndash; first female architecture graduate at McGill and one of the first female registered architects in Canada\n*[[Dimitri Dimakopoulos]] (BArch 1955) &ndash; of [[Affleck, Desbarats, Dimakopoulos, Lebensold, Sise]], designed [[Place Ville-Marie]]<ref name=\"Collectif2012\">{{cite book|last=Collectif|first=|title=Place Ville Marie: Montreal's Shining Landmark|date=21 September 2012|publisher=Qu\u00e9bec Amerique|language=English|isbn=9782764411728|page=207}}</ref> and [[1000 de La Gauchetiere]]\n*[[Dorice Constance Brown Walford|Dorice Walford]] (MArch 1958) &ndash; one of the first Canadian women in architecture to specialize in designing buildings for institutions\n*Eric Bunge (BSc[Arch] 1989, BArch 1991) &ndash; [[American Institute of Architects|FAIA]], co-founder of nARCHITECTS, 2005 Prix de Rome winner<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arch.columbia.edu/faculty/169-eric-bunge|title=Eric Bunge|publisher=Columbia GSAPP|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Frances Bronet]] (BSc[Arch] 1977, BArch 1978) &ndash; president of the [[Pratt Institute]] in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pratt.edu/the-institute/administration-resources/office-of-the-president/about/|title=Pratt Institute {{!}} The Institute {{!}} Administration and Resources {{!}} Office of the President {{!}} About Frances Bronet|website=www.pratt.edu|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n*[[Gavin Affleck]] (BArch 1985) &ndash; architect and son of [[Raymond Affleck|Ray Affleck]]\n*[[Gluskin Sheff|Gerald Sheff]] (BArch 1964) &ndash; founder of [[Gluskin Sheff + Associates Inc.]] and benefactor of the Gluskin Sheff Travel Scholarship at McGill\n*[[Gregory Henriquez]] (MArch 1988) &ndash; Vancouver-based architect<ref>{{cite web|url=https://henriquezpartners.com/teams/gregory-henriquez/|title=Gregory Henriquez|publisher=Henriquez Partners|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Arcop|Guy Desbarats]] (BArch 1948) &ndash; co-founder of Montreal-based architectural firm [[Arcop]]\n*Hal Ingberg (BSc[Arch] 1983, BArch 1985) &ndash; architect of [[Palais des congr\u00e8s de Montr\u00e9al]], 1993 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=Alumni2>{{cite web|url=https://mcgillnews.mcgill.ca/s/1762/news/interior.aspx?sid=1762&gid=2&pgid=551|title=City builders, McGill Alumni|author=Daniel McCabe|publisher=McGill News Alumni Magazine|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Harry Mayerovitch]] (BArch 1933) &ndash; architect, artist and cartoonist\n*Howard Davies (BSc[Arch] 1982, BArch 1983) &ndash; Professor of Practice at the School, co-founder of Atelier Big City, 1998 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=AtelierBigCity /><ref name=Faculty />\n*[[Janet Leys Shaw Mactavish]] (BArch 1947) &ndash; architect of the [[McIntyre Medical Sciences Building]] at McGill<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=i8oVMPqR3BIC&pg=PA75&lpg=PA75&dq=Janet+Leys+Shaw+Mactavish+mcgill&source=bl&ots=V7uLYkgbX_&sig=ACfU3U392NVXQ9W4TnXnNe4d9rbuMteJ-Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjX9szr0o7oAhX0oFwKHa8hDU4Q6AEwAnoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Janet%20Leys%20Shaw%20Mactavish%20mcgill&f=false|author=Annmarie Adams, Peta Tancred|title=Designing Women: Gender and the Architectural Profession, Heritage Series|page=75|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=2000|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[John Campbell Merrett]] (BArch 1931) &ndash; staff architect for [[Canadian National Railway]] and town planner of [[Pointe-Claire, Quebec]]\n*[[Karl Fischer (architect)|Karl Fischer]] (BSc[Arch] 1971, BArch 1972) &ndash; New York-based architect and benefactor of the Karl Fischer Scholarship at McGill\n*Katsuhiro Yamazaki (BSc[Arch] 1994, BArch 1996) &ndash; co-founder of Atelier TAG, 2007 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=Alumni2 />\n*[[Lucien Lagrange]] (BArch 1972) &ndash; former partner at [[Skidmore, Owings & Merrill]] and founder of [[Lucien Lagrange Architects|Lucien Lagrange & Associates]]\n*[[Ludger Lemieux]] &ndash; architect known for his Art Deco buildings in Montreal, notably [[Atwater Market]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/archives/379526/ludger-and-paul-m-lemieux-fonds|title=Ludger and Paul M. Lemieux fonds|publisher=Canadian Centre for Architecture|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Manon Asselin (BSc[Arch] 1990, BArch 1992, MArch 2001) &ndash; co-founder of Atelier TAG, 2007 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=Alumni2 />\n*[[Marc Mayer]] (B.A. 1984) &ndash; arts manager and curator\n*[[Maxwell M. Kalman]] (BArch 1931) &ndash; designed over 1,100 projects in Quebec, including Canada's first shopping centre\n*[[Melvin Charney]] (BArch 1958) &ndash; architect known for designing the [[sculpture garden]] at the [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]]\n*[[Moshe Safdie]] (MArch 1961) &ndash; architect of [[Habitat 67]], [[Marina Bay Sands]], [[Jewel Changi Airport]] and the [[Montreal Museum of Fine Arts]]\n*[[Peter Oberlander]] (BArch 1945) &ndash; architect and Canada's first professor of Urban and Regional Planning\n*Rami Bebawi (BSc[Arch] 1999, MArch 2001) &ndash; co-founder of [[KANVA Architecture]], 2017 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=Alumni2 /> \n*Randy Cohen (BSc[Arch] 1981, BArch 1982) &ndash; co-founder of Atelier Big City, 1998 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=AtelierBigCity />\n*[[Raymond Affleck]] (BArch 1947) &ndash; co-founder of [[Arcop]]\n*[[Raymond Moriyama]] (MArch 1957) &ndash; architect of [[Ottawa City Hall]], [[Bata Shoe Museum]] and [[Scarborough City Centre]]\n*[[WZMH Architects|Ren\u00e9 Menk\u00e8s]] (BArch 1955) &ndash; co-founder of [[WZMH Architects]], architect of [[CN Tower]]\n*[[Robert John Pratt]] (BArch 1933) &ndash; politician and architect\n*[[Robert Jolicoeur]], landscape architect and designer of [[International Federation for Equestrian Sports|FEI]] equestrian show jumping courses\n*[[Robert Libman]] (BArch 1985) &ndash; politician and architect\n*Robert Magne (BArch 1976) &ndash; architect of the [[Bell Centre]]<ref name=Alumni2 />\n*Robert Mellin (MArch 1984) &ndash; president of the [[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mcgill.ca/architecture/channels/news/prof-robert-mellin-elected-president-rca-268189|title=Prof. Robert Mellin elected President of RCA|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture, McGill University|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Robert Schofield Morris]] (BArch 1923) &ndash; architect and [[Royal Gold Medal|RIBA Gold Medal]] recipient<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionaryofarchitectsincanada.org/node/2338|title=Morris, Robert Schofield|publisher=Biographical Dictionary of Architects in Canada: 1800-1950|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n*St\u00e9phane Pratte (BSc[Arch] 1989, BArch 1991) &ndash; co-founder of Atelier In Situ, 2001 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=Alumni2 />\n*[[Ted Remerowski]] (BSc[Arch] 1970) &ndash; film producer\n*Tudor Radulescu (BSc[Arch] 1998, MArch 1991) &ndash; co-founder of [[KANVA Architecture]], 2017 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=Alumni2 />\n*[[Witold Rybczynski]] (BArch 1966, MArch 1972) &ndash; architectural writer/researcher\n<ref name=History /><ref name=Alumni />\n\n===Current and former faculty===\n*[[Alberto P\u00e9rez-G\u00f3mez]] &ndash; professor (current)<ref name=Faculty />\n*[[Annmarie Adams]] &ndash; associate professor (current) and former director of the School<ref name=Faculty />\n*[[Eva Vecsei|Andre Vecsei]] &ndash; visiting professor\n*[[Andrew Taylor (architect)|Andrew Taylor]] &ndash; taught freehand and model drawing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/taylor_andrew_thomas_16E.html|title=TAYLOR, Sir ANDREW THOMAS|publisher=University of Toronto/Universit\u00e9 Laval|website=Dictionary of Canadian Biography|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Arthur Lismer]] &ndash; member of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]], taught from 1941 to 1955<ref name=Lismer />\n*[[Dan Hanganu]] &ndash; architect of the [[Pointe-\u00e0-Calli\u00e8re Museum]] and the [[HEC Montr\u00e9al]] building\n*Douglas Shadbolt &ndash; director of architecture schools at [[Technical University of Nova Scotia]] (1961\u20131968), [[Carleton University]] (1968\u20131979) and [[University of British Columbia]] (1979\u20131990),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/article/douglas-shadbolt|title=Douglas Shadbolt|publisher=The Canadian Encyclopedia|author=Michael Mcmordie|date=2013|accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref> taught at McGill's School of Architecture from 1958 to 1961\n*[[Ernest Cormier]] &ndash; taught from 1919 to 1920<ref name=Cormier />\n*Frederic Lasserre &ndash; founder of the School of Architecture at the [[University of British Columbia]]\n*[[:fr:Fred Lebensold|Fred Lebensold]] &ndash; co-founder of [[Arcop]], taught from 1949 to 1955\n*[[Gavin Affleck]] &ndash; visiting professor\n*[[Gentile Tondino]] &ndash; renowned artist, taught from 1959 to 1999\n*[[Saucier + Perrotte#Founders|Gilles Saucier]] &ndash; founder of [[Saucier + Perrotte]], designed the [[Elizabeth Wirth Music Building]] on McGill campus, course lecturer (current)\n*[[Arcop|Guy Desbarats]] &ndash; co-founder of [[Arcop|Affleck, Desbarats, Dimakopoulos, Lebensold, Sise]]\n*[[Harold Lea Fetherstonhaugh]] &ndash; architect of many buildings on McGill's campus, including Douglas Hall and [[McGill University School of Religious Studies|William and Henry Birks Building]]\n*[[Hazen Sise]] &ndash; co-founder of [[Arcop|Affleck, Desbarats, Dimakopoulos, Lebensold, Sise]]\n*[[John Bland (architect)|John Bland]] &ndash; architect, served as director of the School for 31 years\n*[[John C. Parkin]] &ndash; co-founder of [[List of works by John B. Parkin Associates|John B. Parkin Associates]], visiting professor\n*Matthew Lella &ndash; principal at [[Diamond Schmitt Architects]], visiting professor\n*[[Michael Jemtrud]] &ndash; associate professor (current)<ref name=Faculty />\n*[[Moshe Safdie]] &ndash; visiting professor\n*[[Percy Nobbs]] &ndash; architect of many buildings on McGill's campus, including the [[Redpath Library]] and [[Osler Library]] buildings, taught from 1903 to 1939<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archivalcollections.library.mcgill.ca/index.php/percy-erskine-nobbs|title=Fonds 1 - Percy Erskine Nobbs Fonds|publisher=McGill Archival Collections Catalogue|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Peter Guo-hua Fu &ndash; Professor of Practice (current), eponym of the Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture\n*[[Peter Rose (architect)|Peter Rose]] &ndash; architect of [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-VZuLglXfrMC&pg=PA241&lpg=PA241&dq=Peter+Rose+mcgill&source=bl&ots=lrFArSFKLW&sig=ACfU3U3xmfYaMVZl6OicBeR2vwe95QW-xg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjosf_HzI7oAhXNT8AKHRRYBfQQ6AEwAXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=Peter%20Rose%20mcgill&f=false|author=Louise Pelletier, Alberto P\u00e9rez-G\u00f3mez|title=Architecture, Ethics, and Technology|page=241|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press - MQUP|year=1994|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Ramsay Traquair (architect)|Ramsay Traquair]] &ndash; third director of the School, taught from 1913 to 1939\n*[[Raymond Affleck|Ray Affleck]] &ndash; co-founder of [[Arcop]], visiting professor from 1967 to 1975<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/archives/225767/ray-affleck-fonds|title=Ray Affleck fonds|publisher=CCA|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Ricardo L. Castro]] &ndash; associate professor (current) since 1983<ref name=Faculty />\n*[[Stewart Henbest Capper]] &ndash; first director of the School, taught from 1896 to 1903\n*[[Warren Chalk]] &ndash; founding member of [[Archigram]], visiting professor\n<ref name=History /><ref name=Alumni /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/sheffprofessor#sheff2006|title=Gerald Sheff Visiting Professorship in Architecture|website=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|publisher=McGill University|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada}}\n* [[List of architecture schools#North America|List of architecture schools in Canada]]\n* [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]]\n* [[McCall MacBain Arts Building]]\n* [[Stephen Leacock Building]]\n* [[Elizabeth Wirth Music Building]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|McGill University}}\n{{Scholia|organization}}\n*[https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture Official Website]\n*[http://www.aias.org/ AIAS Official Website]\n\n{{McGill}}\n{{Navboxes\n|titlestyle = background:#CD202C; color:#ffffff; border:1px solid #000000;\n{{Montreal}}\n{{Qc Uni}}\n{{U15}}\n{{Association of American Universities}}\n{{Faith and Globalisation Network}}\n{{Universities Research Association}}\n{{Can-sem}}\n{{Universities in Canada |state=collapsed}}\n}}\n[[Category:McGill University]]\n[[Category:1896 establishments in Quebec]]\n[[Category:Architecture schools in Canada]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1896]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n|name        = McGill School of Architecture\n|image       = McGill_School_of_Architecture_logo.jpg\n|image_size  = 250px\n|caption     = Macdonald-Harrington Building\n|established = {{start date and age|1896}}\n|type        = [[Public university|Public]]\n|parent      = [[McGill University Faculty of Engineering|Faculty of Engineering]]<br>[[McGill University]]\n|faculty     = 44<ref name=Faculty>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/faculty|title=Faculty and Staff, Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n|director    = Martin Bressani\n|students    = 273 (Fall 2019)<ref name=Enrollment>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/es/registration-statistics|title=Enrollment Reports|publisher=McGill University|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n|undergrad   = 163 \n|postgrad    = 90 \n|doctoral    = 20<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/phd-students|title=Current Ph.D. students|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n|city        = [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]], [[Montreal]]\n|province    = [[Quebec]]\n|country     = [[Canada]]\n|coordinates = {{coord |45.5053|-73.5758|type:edu_region:CA-QC|display=inline,title}}\n|campus      = [[urban area|Urban]] \n|free_label  = Student Life\n|free        = [[Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture#Student life|ASA]], [[Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture#Student life|AIAS]], [[Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture#Student life|GASA]]\n|website     = {{url|https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''McGill School of Architecture''' (also known as the '''Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture''') is a constituent of the [[McGill University Faculty of Engineering|Faculty of Engineering]] at [[McGill University]] in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]]. Founded in 1896 by [[William Christopher Macdonald|Sir William Macdonald]], it is among the oldest [[architecture schools]] in [[North America]].<ref name=History>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history|title=History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref> The School offers accredited professional and post-professional programs ranging from undergraduate to PhD levels,<ref name=Programs>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/programs|title=Programs|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref> with the smallest entering class of any accredited architecture school in Canada.<ref name=Stats>{{cite web|url=https://www.acsa-arch.org/resources/data-resources/vital-statistics-on-canadian-schools-of-architecture/|title=Vital Statistics on Canadian Schools of Architecture|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> Since its founding, the School has established an international reputation and a record of producing leading professionals and researchers who have helped shape the field of architecture, including [[Moshe Safdie]], [[Arthur Erickson]], [[Raymond Moriyama]] and the founders of [[Arcop]].{{NoteTag|The founders of Arcop include [[Ray Affleck]], Guy Desbarats, Jean Michaud, [[:fr:Fred Lebensold|Fred Lebensold]], [[Hazen Sise]] and [[Dimitri Dimakopoulos]], all graduates and/or professors at the School of Architecture at some point.<ref name=Arcop>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/archives/379565/affleck-desbarats-dimakopoulos-lebensold-sise-fonds|title=Affleck, Desbarats, Dimakopoulos, Lebensold, Sise fonds|publisher=Canadian Centre for Architecture|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>}}<ref name=Alumni>{{cite web| url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews|title=Alumni Interviews|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe School of Architecture is housed in the [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]], designed by [[Andrew Taylor (architect)|Sir Andrew Taylor]], on the McGill University downtown campus. The [[McGill University Faculty of Engineering#School of Urban Planning|School of Urban Planning]] occupies the fourth floor.<ref name=CAC>{{cite web|url=http://cac.mcgill.ca/campus/buildings/Macdonald-Harrington.html|title=Macdonald-Harrington Building (formerly Macdonald Chemistry Building)|publisher=Canadian Architecture Collection, McGill Archives|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> The School also operates many auxiliary facilities, including workshops, laser cutting and 3D-printing facilities, research labs and various libraries and collections both within the Macdonald-Harrington Building and elsewhere on McGill's campus. The School is accredited by the [[Professional requirements for architects#Canada|Canadian Architectural Certification Board]] (CACB) and is recognized in the United States by the [[National Council of Architectural Registration Boards]] (NCARB).<ref name=Accreditation>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/programs/accreditation|title=Accreditation|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture, McGill University|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn September 26, 2017, the School was renamed the Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture following a [[Canadian dollar|C]]$12&nbsp;million gift from architect and McGill graduate Peter Fu.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.architectmagazine.com/design/chinese-architect-peter-guo-hua-fu-donated-12-million-to-the-mcgill-school-of-architecture_o| title=Chinese Architect Peter Guo-hua Fu Donated $12 Million to the McGill School of Architecture | publisher=Architect Magazine |author=Ayda Ayoubi| year=2017 |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nMcGill's School of Architecture, founded in 1896, is one of the oldest architecture schools in North America and the second to be established in Canada.<!-- University of Toronto had the first architecture program in Canada (1890)--><ref name=History /> It began as a [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]] style school based in the [[Arts and Crafts movement]], and became a [[Bauhaus]]-based institution under new directorship after [[World War&nbsp;II]]. The School was the first in Canada to offer a graduate planning program and a Ph.D. in Architecture.<ref name=CanadianArchitect>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/glaciermedia/docs/canadian_architect_october_2014|title=State of the Schools - Canadian Architect October Issue 2014|page=18|publisher=Canadian Architect|date=October 2014|author=Annmarie Adams|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Early history===\nIn 1890, the [[Ordre des architectes du Qu\u00e9bec|Province of Quebec Association of Architects]] adopted a constitution requiring compulsory examination for people in Quebec who wished to become professional architects. This created a need for more systematic architectural education, and the absence of such opportunities caused many aspiring Canadian architects to study in the United States, where ten architecture schools had already been established.<ref name=History /> Canada did not yet have any formal architectural education, and the only forms of architectural education in Montreal were periodical lectures by local practising architects at McGill's affiliated religious colleges. This new need for architectural education is an important factor that led to the founding of the School of Architecture at McGill University.\n[[File:William Christopher Macdonald.jpg|thumb|upright|[[William Christopher Macdonald|Sir William C. Macdonald]], 4th [[List of McGill University people#List of chancellors|Chancellor of McGill University]], created a Chair in Architecture at McGill in 1896.]]\n\nIn 1896, [[William Christopher Macdonald|Sir William C. Macdonald]] created a chair in architecture at McGill which was led by [[Stewart Henbest Capper]]. At this time, the School offered a four-year course to prepare students for professional accreditation. The first graduating class was composed of three students: George Taylor Hyde, Norman M. McLeod and Frank Peder. Professor Capper gave all lectures in architecture, and Henry F. Armstrong, the only other full-time professor, taught art classes and modelling.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/beginning|title=The beginning with Stewart H. Capper, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe second director of the School, [[Percy Nobbs]], arrived at McGill in 1903 to only two students: Gordon H. Blackader and H.&nbsp;E. Shorey. He divided the four-year course into two streams, the BArch degree and the BSc degree in Architectural Engineering. Three new staff were hired in 1906, and three years later, [[Philip J. Turner]] joined the faculty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/nobbs|title=Legacy of Nobbs, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1913, [[Ramsay Traquair (architect)|Ramsay Traquair]] became the new director of the School. He designed the Baillie library window and the flag above the [[McCall MacBain Arts Building|Arts Building]] at McGill, which still remain today.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/traquair|title= Legacy of Traquair, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/McGillLibrary-cac_finding-aid_ramsay-traquair-book1-guide-18112/page/n21/mode/2up|title=Ramsay Traquair and his successors : guide to the Archive|date=1987|publisher=Blackader-Lauterman Library of Architecture and Art, McGill University|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>{{page needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:Arts Building, McGill University.jpg|thumb|upright|The McGill flag, designed by [[Ramsay Traquair (architect)|Ramsay Traquair]] and presented to McGill in 1921, flown above the [[McCall MacBain Arts Building|Arts Building]].]]\n\nIn 1921, the School had its first \"sketching school\" in [[Quebec City]], a tradition that has been carried on annually to various destinations since as a credited course. [[Arthur Lismer]], a founding member of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]], taught this course at the School for over a decade starting in 1941.<ref name=Lismer>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/library/channels/event/exhibition-arthur-lismers-mcgill-sketchbook-240235|title=Exhibition: Arthur Lismer\u2019s McGill Sketchbook|publisher=McGill Library|year=2015|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 1939, Turner succeeded Traquair, who had completed a 26-year tenure as director of the School. At this time, the principal of McGill, [[Lewis Williams Douglas]], considered phasing out architectural education at the university due to low enrollment; however he faced a great deal of backlash from Turner and several famous architects from Montreal, and eventually abandoned the idea. Among these architects was [[Ernest Cormier]], who taught at the School from 1919 to 1920.<ref name=Cormier>{{cite web|url=https://www.pc.gc.ca/en/culture/clmhc-hsmbc/res/doc/information-backgrounder/Ernest_Cormier|title=Ernest Cormier (1885-1980)|publisher=Parks Canada|accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nUnder Turner's tenure, the door to co-ed education was opened, and in 1943 [[Catherine Mary Wisnicki]] became the School's first female graduate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/turner|title=Legacy of Turner, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> Wisnicki would also become the fourth female member of the [[Ontario Association of Architects]], which was founded in 1889.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Ontario Association of Architects|journal=Canadian Architect and Builder|date=April 1889|volume=2|issue=4|page=40|url=https://archive.org/stream/canadianarchitec01onta#page/n29/mode/1up|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Mid-century===\nFollowing the retirement of Turner as director of the School of Architecture, [[John Bland (architect)|John Bland]] became director in 1941. In 1945, a new five-year program was adopted for the next two decades. After the [[World War Two|war]], the School of Architecture increased its staff and doubled its physical accommodation due to the surge in university enrollment. This required the School to briefly use McGill's [[Dawson College]], a [[satellite campus]] in St. Jean, Quebec, to accommodate its students. By 1947, the School had become so cramped that a former Victorian residential building on University Street was vacated to make room for the School's students.<ref name=McGillForties />\n\nAround this time, Professor Frederic Lasserre of McGill's School of Architecture left the university to establish a new School of Architecture at the [[University of British Columbia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sala.ubc.ca/about/history|title=History|publisher=University of British Columbia School of Architecture + Landscape Architecture|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> and invited McGill Architecture graduates [[Catherine Mary Wisnicki]], [[Peter Oberlander]] and [[Arthur Erickson]] to teach at his new school. \n\nIn 1946, [[Harold Spence-Sales]] was appointed Associate Professor of Design. He and Bland established the first post-graduate architecture and planning program in Canada. Enrollment had grown from 23 students in 1941 to 133 full-time students in the 1949/1950 academic year.<ref name=McGillForties>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/forties|title=The School with John Bland:1940s, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> Beginning in this academic year, the professional program was extended to six years, with first-year students following the engineering curriculum.\n\nDuring the early 1950s, three new teachers were added to the faculty, including Hazen Sise and Guy Desbarats who would later found [[Arcop]] with Fred Lebensold, [[Ray Affleck]], and [[Dimitri Dimakopoulos]]&nbsp;\u2013 all former students or teachers of the School.<ref name=Arcop />\n\nEnrollment was steady during the 1950s due to the limitations of physical space, but a four-story expansion of the McConnell Building in the 1960s allowed for growth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/fifties|title=The School with John Bland:1950s, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1961, [[Moshe Safdie]] published his master's thesis which became the basis for [[Habitat 67]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} That year, McGill Professor Douglas Shadbolt left the School to found the first architecture program at the Nova Scotia Technical College (later known as [[Technical University of Nova Scotia|Technical University of Nova Scotia]] [TUNS]) in [[Halifax, Canada|Halifax]], and 8 years later founded the School of Architecture (later the Azrieli School of Architecture and Urbanism) at [[Carleton University]] in [[Ottawa, Ontario|Ottawa]].<ref name=Shadbolt>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/douglas-shadbolt|title=Douglas Shadbolt|publisher=The Canadian Encyclopedia|author=Michael McMordie|date=16 December 2013|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, [[John C. Parkin]], [[Harry Mayerovitch]] and Victor Prus, all distinguished practicing architects, joined the faculty as visiting professors. In the following years, [[Ray Affleck]], Fred Lebensold, [[Eva Vecsei|Andre Vecsei]], [[Warren Chalk]] and <!--Moshe--> Safdie also became visiting professors.<ref name=McGillSixties />\n\nIn the late 1960s, the six-year architecture program became a four-year program with the introduction of [[CEGEP]]s in Quebec.<ref name=McGillSixties>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/sixties|title=The School with John Bland:1960s, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===1970\u2013present===\nIn 1970, Spence-Sales retired from the faculty. Later that year, the graduate planning program was reorganized by Professor David Farley, which resulted in the establishment of the independent School of Urban Planning on the fourth floor of the [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]]. Over the next decade and a half, the School changed directorship three times, with Professor Norbert Schoenauer heading the School from 1972 until 1975, Professor Derek Drummond from 1975 until 1985 and Professor Bruce Anderson in 1985.<ref name=Highlights /> \n\nIn 1987, the School moved from the Engineering building to the Macdonald-Harrington Building. Macdonald-Harrington was initially named the Macdonald Chemistry Building but was renamed after Bernard Harrington, the building's first chemistry professor. The building is one of the many donations made by [[William Christopher Macdonald|Sir William Macdonald]] and was designed by Sir Andrew Taylor to accommodate the Departments of Chemistry and Mining in 1896. The building was renovated for architecture and urban planning students by architects [[Arcop]] in 1987.<ref name=CAC />\n\nIn 1989, the PhD in Architecture was introduced as an ''ad hoc'' program. In 1990, Derek Drummond returned for another six years as the School's director, replaced by Professor David Covo in 1996. In 1997, the PhD program was officially approved by the Minister of Education as the first in Canada,<ref name=CanadianArchitect /> and the School had its first PhD graduate, Lily Chi. In 1999, the professional BArch degree was replaced by the new MArchI professional degree, leaving the undergraduate BSc in architecture. Two years later, the School graduated its first class in the MArchI program.<ref name=Highlights /> \n\nIn 2003, philanthropist [[David Azrieli]] endowed an annual lecture at the School, called the [[McGill School of Architecture#Lecture Series|David J. Azrieli Lecture Series]], which has attracted many celebrity [[starchitect|starchitects]] to the School, including seven [[Pritzker Prize]] laureates. \n\nAfter an 11-year tenure as director, Covo stepped down and Professor [[Michael Jemtrud]] became director of the School in 2007. The next year, Jemtrud founded the Facility for Architectural Research in Media and Mediation (FARMM) at the School of Architecture with more than $1&nbsp;million in funding from the [[Canada Foundation for Innovation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ca.linkedin.com/company/facility-for-architectural-research-in-media-and-mediation-farmm-|title=Facility for Architectural Research in Media and Mediation (FARMM)|website=LinkedIn|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> FARMM produced many award-winning projects and serves as the research hub for the School.<ref name=FARMM>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/farmm|title=Facility for Architectural Research in Media Mediation|publisher=McGill University|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Professor [[Annmarie Adams]] became the first female director of the School of Architecture. Since 2015, the director has been Professor Martin Bressani.<ref name=Highlights>{{cite web| url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school|title=Highlights of the School's History|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Directors===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Director !! Tenure<ref name=Highlights />\n|-\n| [[Stewart Henbest Capper]] || 1896\u20131903 \n|-\n| [[Percy Nobbs]] || 1903\u20131913\n|-\n| [[Ramsay Traquair (architect)|Ramsay Traquair]] || 1913\u20131939\n|-\n| [[Philip J. Turner]] || 1939\u20131941\n|-\n| [[John Bland (architect)|John Bland]] || 1941\u20131972\n|-\n| Norbert Schoenauer || 1972\u20131975\n|-\n| Derek Drummond || 1975\u20131985\n|-\n| Bruce Anderson || 1985\u20131990\n|-\n| Derek Drummond || 1990\u20131996\n|-\n| David Covo || 1996\u20132007\n|-\n| [[Michael Jemtrud]] || 2007\u20132011\n|-\n| [[Annmarie Adams]] || 2011\u20132015\n|-\n|Martin Bressani\n|2015\u2013present\n|}\n\n==Buildings and resources==\n===Macdonald-Harrington Building===\n[[File:McGill University Building3.jpg|thumb|upright|The [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]], home to the McGill School of Architecture since 1987.]]\nThe [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]] is the home of the Peter Guo-hua School of Architecture, and also contains the [[McGill University Faculty of Engineering#School of Urban Planning|School of Urban Planning]] on the fourth level.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/engineering/faculty-staff/facilities/buildings/macdonald-harrington|title=Macdonald-Harrington Building|publisher=McGill Faculty of Engineering|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> As architecture students progress through the years of the undergraduate program, they move through the design studios as well, with each year's respective studio located on a different level of the Macdonald-Harrington Building. The Master's studios are located on the top level, while the PhD studios are located on the same level as the U1 studios and the School's administration. The ground level, which can be accessed from the Frank Dawson Adams (FDA) building,<ref name=Map>{{cite web|url=https://maps.mcgill.ca/?lat=45.50559139299993&lng=-73.57612234168278&z=16.000000&id=MacdonaldHarr|title=McGill University Interactive Campus Map|publisher=McGill Campus Maps|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> contains the lecture hall known as \"G-10\", one of the only lecture rooms in Macdonald-Harrington that is not exclusive to architecture or urban planning students. G-10 also hosts [[McGill School of Architecture#Lecture series|the School's lecture series]].<ref name=LectureSeries>{{cite web| url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/news-events/lectures|title=Lecture Series|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n \nThe ground floor also contains the ASA Supply Store where students can purchase drafting kits,<ref name=SupplyStore>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/asa.supplystore/|title=ASA Supply Store|publisher=Architecture Students' Association|website=Facebook|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> as well as the architecture student lounge, known as the \"Cellar\", which unlike most lounges at McGill, is accessible 24/7 to architecture students.<ref name=Cellar>{{cite web|url=https://eus.wiki/Departmental_Lounges|title=Departmental Lounges|website=EUS (Engineering Undergraduate Society) Wiki|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> The first floor, above the ground level, contains the U2 studio as well as three crit rooms, the largest among them dubbed the \"exhibition room\" due to its common hosting of exhibitions of students' and outside guests' work. The U3 studios, used by students in their final year of undergraduate studies, are located on the third floor of Macdonald-Harrington.\n\nAll of the model-making resources students need are located within the architecture building, and apart from materials and printing, which must be purchased, all resources can be used free-of-charge and are exclusive to architecture students.\n\n====Workshop====\nThe workshop is located in the basement and ground floor of the Macdonald-Harrington building, and provides students with all of their model-making needs. The workshop contains various equipment and power tools for working with wood, plaster, glass, acrylics and metal, and also contains other facilities, including a fumehood for sandblasting, spray painting, casting and mould-making.\n\nWorkshop facilities include a Laser Cutting Room with three Universal Laser Cutter machines that students can use free-of-charge to cut and engrave acrylic, MDF, wood, styrene and other sheet materials. The workshop also includes 3D-printing machines, two of which are located inside the U3 studios on the third floor. <ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/workshop|title=Workshop facilities|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nMcGill University as a whole has a 3D-printing hub called \"the Cube\" which offers 3D-printing services to McGill students.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://uprint3d.xyz/|title=The Cube, McGill University|accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Media Centre====\nThe Media Centre is located in the Macdonald-Harrington building and is available exclusively to architecture students, faculty and staff at McGill.  \nThe Centre includes a traditional dark room for developing film photographs, a photography studio/light room for students to photograph their work as well as a printing room with multiple large format printers and scanners. The Media Centre also lends out digital cameras, lenses, tripods and light tents to students.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/media-centre|title=Media Centre|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref><!--cleaned up the copyright issues-->\n\n====FARMM====\nThe Facility for Architectural Research in Media and Mediation (FARMM) is the research hub of the McGill School of Architecture, located on the first floor of the Macdonald-Harrington Building. Founded in 2008 by the director of the School at the time, [[Michael Jemtrud]], with over $1&nbsp;million in funding from the [[Canada Foundation for Innovation]], FARMM's mandate is to explore collaborative design utilizing advanced technologies in computation and networking. The facility links researchers and students from the School of Architecture to other researchers around the world, and contains state-of-the-art networking, simulation and imaging, and fabrication infrastructure.<ref name=FARMM />\n\n=== John Bland Canadian Architecture Collection===\nThe [[Canadian Architecture Collection]] (CAC) is one of the [[McGill University Library|McGill Libraries]]' Special Collections. Students and professors at these schools are required to document their work and entrust it with the Canadian Architecture Collection for safe-keeping. \n\nThe Collection currently consists of over 150,000 drawings, 25,000 photographs and 11,000 slides, 190 models, 300 maps and 400 metres of papers of nineteenth- and twentieth-century architects in Canada.<ref name=JBCAC>{{cite web| url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/collection|title=John Bland Canadian Architecture Collection|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref> The largest fond of major Canadian architects is that of [[Moshe Safdie]], who donated his archives to the collection with an ongoing bequest since 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cac.mcgill.ca/moshesafdie/history.html|title=The Moshe Safdie Archive|publisher=McGill Library|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> The CAC also includes 770 papers from the course \"History of Architecture in Canada\".<ref name=JBCAC />\n\n=== Architecture Slide Library===\nThe Architecture Slide Library contains more than 40,000 images, of which nineteenth- and twentieth-century images are the most heavily used. They are stored in Room 310 of the Macdonald-Harrington building, while slides from earlier periods are stored in the Media Centre.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/slides|title=Architecture Slide Library|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Orson Wheeler Architectural Model Collection===\nThe Orson Wheeler Architectural Model Collection contains over two hundred scale  architectural models of structures from around the world. The models were created between 1940 and 1990 by Orson Wheeler, a sculptor and former professor at McGill's School of Architecture.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/model|title=Orson Wheeler Architectural Model Collection|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nA small collection of his works are on display in the front vestibule of the Macdonald-Harrington building.\n\n=== Blackader-Lauterman Library of Architecture and Art===\nThe Blackader-Lauterman Library of Architecture and Art is the University's parent library for the Schools of Architecture and Urban Planning, and is located on the upper floor of the Humanities and Social Sciences Library, one of thirteen branches of the McGill Library.\n\nThe library was established through a donation from the family of the late Gordon H. Blackader, one of the first students to study at the School of Architecture whose life was cut short during World War&nbsp;I. The library was renamed the Blackader-Lauterman Library of Architecture and Art during the 1940s after the family of sculptor [[Dinah Lauterman]] donated in her memory. \n\nThe library contains over 79,000 monographs and journal subscriptions, and has a substantial collection of over 3000 rare books from 1511 to 2009 housed in the [[Rare Books and Special Collections Library]] at McGill. This includes a fine collection of original works by [[G.&nbsp;B. Piranesi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/library|title=Blackader-Lauterman Library of Architecture and Art|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Centre Canadien Architecture Montreal.JPG|thumb|220px|right|[[Canadian Centre for Architecture]], view of Shaughnessy House.]]\n===Canadian Centre for Architecture===\nStudents are always welcome to visit the [[Canadian Centre for Architecture|Canadian Centre for Architecture (CCA)]], which houses one of the largest architectural design collections in the world,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/canadian-heritage/news/2019/02/the-government-of-canada-supports-the-canadian-centre-for-architecture.html|title=The Government of Canada supports the Canadian Centre for Architecture|publisher=Government of Canada|date=11 February 2019|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> just a 20-minute walk away from the downtown campus. The CCA collaborates regularly with the McGill School of Architecture, and organized the 2019 CCA Interuniversity [[Charrette]] with the School, which took place over a week in November and involved more than 10 universities in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.qc.ca/charrette/2019/en/index.html|title=About, CCA Interuniversity Charette|publisher=Canadian Centre for Architecture|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n===Architecture Students' Association (ASA)===\nThe Architecture Students' Association (ASA) is a non-profit student-run society within the School of Architecture. The society represents all undergraduate students in the School of Architecture, organizes student activities and affairs and acts as a voice for students in issues at McGill.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://mcgill.ca/engineering/students/undergraduate/student-life/student-groups-associations|title=Student Groups & Associations, Faculty of Engineering|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> The ASA is chaired by the President and run by an Executive Council composed of six Vice-President portfolios: Academic, Internal, External, Administration, Finance and Student Life. A student representative from each undergraduate year is also elected to sit on the Council. \n\nPart of the ASA's mandate is to maintain the ASA Supply Store where students can purchase drafting kits as well as the architecture lounge, also known as the \"Cellar\".<ref name=Cellar />\n\n===Graduate Architecture Students' Association (GASA)===\nThe McGill Graduate Architecture Students' Association (GASA) is a student-run society representing all graduate students at the School of Architecture. GASA is known to hold \"Late Night\" events on Thursdays, popular among students from all programs in the School.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.mcgill.ca/engage/overview/faculty-and-school-associations/graduate-faculty-and-school-associations|title=Graduate Faculty and School Associations, Engage McGill|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===American Institute of Architecture Students (AIAS)===\nAs of 2019, the School of Architecture has established a chapter of the [[American Institute of Architecture Students]], an international, non-profit, student-run organization dedicated to providing progressive programs, information and resources on critical issues to architecture students.<ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.aias.org/chapter/mcgill-university/|title=McGill University, Northeast Quad|publisher=American Institute of Architecture Students/accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Exchange and Study Abroad===\nThe Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture has close ties to several architecture schools across the world and has formal bilateral exchange agreements on a departmental level with seven schools in particular, including [[The Royal Danish Academy of Fine Arts]] in [[Copenhagen]], [[Politecnico di Milano]] in [[Milan]], [[Tongji University]] in [[Shanghai]], [[\u00c9cole Nationale Sup\u00e9rieure d'Architecture de Paris-Belleville]], [[:fr:\u00c9cole nationale sup\u00e9rieure d'architecture de Grenoble|\u00c9cole nationale sup\u00e9rieure d'architecture de Grenoble]], [[Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain]] in [[Brussels]] and [[TU Wien]] in [[Vienna]]. These bilateral agreements make it easy for undergraduate architecture students at McGill to go on exchange.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/files/architecture/bscarch_programadvisingandcourseregistration-fall_2018.pdf|title=B.Sc.(Arch.) program and Architecture Exchange Students (New and Returning Students) - STUDENT EXCHANGES|page=5|publisher=McGill University|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nStudents also have the opportunity to spend an exchange semester abroad at any of McGill University's 160+ partner institutions<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/mcgillabroad/mcgill-students-going-abroad/global-learning-opportunities|title=McGill students going abroad|publisher=McGill Abroad, McGill University|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> as long as they offer architecture exchanges, however these are more difficult to coordinate due to the competitive nature of University-wide exchanges. In addition to the seven schools with whom the School of Architecture has bilateral agreements, architecture students have spent exchange semesters at some of the top architecture schools in the world, including [[The Bartlett]] at [[University College London (UCL)]], [[National University of Singapore]], [[University of Leeds]], [[University of Liverpool]], [[University of Sheffield]] and [[Australian National University]].\n\n==Academics==\nThe School of Architecture offers a professional program in Architecture comprising a Bachelor of Science in Architecture (BSc[Arch]) and professional Master of Architecture (MArch) degree, as well as post-professional graduate programs leading to a Doctor of Philosophy (PhD) and post-professional Master of Architecture (MArch) degree. The School has a reputation for excellence in teaching, with all of its professors being either practicing architects or holding professional degrees and/or PhDs,<ref name=Faculty /> and architecture professors often being awarded teaching awards proportionately more often than other departments within the Faculty of Engineering relative to their respective sizes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/engineering/faculty-staff/teaching-research-and-service-awards|title=Teaching, Research & Service Awards, Faculty of Engineering|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Professional programs===\n* '''BSc(Arch)''' \u2013 3 years, 100 credits\n* '''MArch (Professional)''':\n** Design Studio \u2013 1.5 years, 45 credits, or\n** Design Studio (Directed Research) \u2013 2 years, 60 credits\n\nThe MArch (Professional) degree is accredited by the [[Professional requirements for architects#Canada|Canadian Architectural Certification Board]] (CACB), and is recognized by the [[National Council of Architectural Registration Boards]] (NCARB) in the United States.<ref name=Accreditation />\n\n===Post-professional research programs===\n* '''MArch (Non-Thesis)''':\n** Architectural History and Theory \u2013 45 credits\n** Urban Design and Housing \u2013 45 credits\n* '''PhD'''\n<ref name=Programs />\n\n===Admissions===\nThe McGill School of Architecture has the smallest entering class per degree offered of any architecture school in Canada. With a maximum capacity of 50 undergraduate students in the first year undergraduate studio (BSc[Arch]) and 35 students in both of the Master's (MArch&nbsp;1 and MArch&nbsp;II) studios, the School has one of the most selective and competitive sets of program offerings in the country with one of the lowest overall application-to-acceptance ratios.<ref name=Stats /> \n\nGenerally, about 5\u201310 students from outside Quebec who plan to study architecture for their undergraduate degree will spend their first year at McGill in U0, taking the necessary engineering prerequisites required for the 3-year BSc (Architecture) program at the School of Architecture. Students coming from Quebec [[CEGEP]]s enter directly into the BSc Architecture program, or U1, but are required to have received a [[Diploma of college studies|DEC]] in either pure and applied science or health sciences, as these degrees fulfill the engineering prerequisites for the Architecture program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/programs/professional#application|title=Application procedures|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture, McGill University|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOffers of acceptance into the program are based on a unique review process including an evaluation of a portfolio of works and extracurricular involvement, in addition to grades. In the 2010\u20132011 academic year, there were 687 applications with portfolios to the undergraduate BSc Architecture program with only 51 spaces, giving an overall applications to enrolments ratio of 7.42%.<ref name=Admissions>{{cite web| url=https://info.publicintelligence.net/McGillSoA-AUR.pdf| title=McGill School of Architecture: 2011 Cyclical Academic Unit Review, p.13 Section 2.0: Academic Programs, Teaching and Learning | year=2011 |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref> With the exception of the new Bioengineering degree at McGill, for Quebec [[CEGEP]] students, admissions to the School of Architecture represent the highest average [[R score]] of students accepted into the Faculty of Engineering<ref>{{cite web| url=https://info.publicintelligence.net/McGillSoA-AUR.pdf| title=McGill School of Architecture: 2011 Cyclical Academic Unit Review, p.39 Section 2.7.1 Admissions | year=2011 |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref> however in contrast to the high average R score, the lowest score admitted can sometimes be closer to the engineering average due to the importance of the portfolio in the admissions process.\n\nThe School of Architecture has one of the highest percentages of female representation at McGill, with an overall ratio of female-to-male students of approximately 2:1. As of fall&nbsp;2019, there were 119 female and 44 male undergraduate students, and 54 female and 36 male graduate students enrolled at the School. In some studios, the ratio can be as high as 8:1, such as is the case for the undergraduate class of 2021.<ref name=Enrollment />\n\n==Lecture series==\nEach year, the School of Architecture presents public lectures, exhibitions and symposia showcasing leading architects and important figures in the field. These lectures are organized by various individuals and organizations affiliated with the School. Lecture Series include lunchtime \"Brown Bag\" lectures organized by the McGill Architecture Students' Association, evening lectures sponsored by local Montreal firms such as Provencher Roy & [[NEUF Architect(e)s]],<ref name=LectureSeries /> and most notably, the annual [[David Azrieli|David J. Azrieli]] Lecture in Architecture which has brought in [[starchitect|starchitects]] from all over the world since 2003,<ref name=AzrieliLecture>{{cite web|url=https://mcgill.ca/architecture/news-events/lectures/azrieli|title=David J. Azrieli Lecture in Architecture|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture, McGill University|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> including seven [[Pritzker Prize]] laureates.{{NoteTag|Lecturers at McGill who have won the [[Pritzker Prize]] include [[Carme Pigem]], [[David Adjaye]], [[Thom Mayne]], [[Shigeru Ban]], [[Paulo Mendes da Rocha]], [[Glenn Murcutt]] and [[Jacques Herzog]].<ref name=Pritzker>{{cite web|url=https://www.pritzkerprize.com/laureates|title=Laureates|publisher=The Hyatt Foundation|website=The Pritzker Architecture Prize|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>}}<ref name=Pritzker />\n\nNotable lecturers:<ref name=LectureSeries /><ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n*[[Douglas Cardinal]] (2019\u20132020)\n*[[Carme Pigem]] (2018\u20132019) \n*[[Odile Decq]] (2018\u20132019) \n*[[Shim-Sutcliffe Architects|Brigitte Shim & Howard Sutcliffe]] (2017\u20132018)\n*[[David Adjaye]] (2016\u20132017) \n*[[Caruso St John|Adam Caruso]] (2015\u20132016) \n*[[Bruce Kuwabara]] (2014\u20132015)\n*[[Bjarke Ingels]] (2013\u20132014)\n*[[J\u00fcrgen Mayer]] (2012\u20132013)\n*[[Thom Mayne]] (2011\u20132012)\n*[[Shigeru Ban]] (2010\u20132011)\n*[[Peter Eisenman]] (2009\u20132010)\n*[[Morphosis Architects|Michael Rotondi]] (2008\u20132009)\n*[[Moshe Safdie]] (2007\u20132008)\n*[[Reiser + Umemoto|Nanako Umemoto]] (2007\u20132008)\n*[[Paulo Mendes da Rocha]] (2006\u20132007) \n*[[Glenn Murcutt]] (2005\u20132006) \n*[[Daniel Libeskind]] (2004\u20132005)\n*[[Diamond Schmitt Architects|Jack Diamond]] (2004\u20132005)\n*[[Will Alsop]] (2002\u20132003, 2004\u20132005) \n*[[Steven Holl]] (2003\u20132004)\n*[[Jacques Herzog]] (2002\u20132003) \n\n==Notable alumni and faculty==\n[[File:Raymond Moriyama.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Raymond Moriyama]], renowned architect of the [[Canadian War Museum]] and [[Scarborough Civic Centre]], graduated from McGill's MArch program in 1957.]]\n[[File:Arthur Erickson Portrait, 1984.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Arthur Erickson]], architect of the [[Museum of Glass]] and [[Roy Thompson Hall]], received his BArch degree from McGill in 1950.]]\n[[File:Moshe Safdie.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Moshe Safdie]], architect of [[Marina Bay Sands]] and [[Habitat 67]], which was originally conceived in his Master's thesis at McGill in 1961.]]\n[[File:Arthur Lismer.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Arthur Lismer]], a member of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]], taught History of Art and Theory of Design, Freehand Drawing and Sketching School at the School of Architecture.]]\n[[File:Ernest Cormier.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Ernest Cormier]], renowned Art Deco architect, taught from 1919 to 1920.]]\n===Alumni===\n*[[Caruso St John|Adam Caruso]] (BArch 1986) &ndash; co-founder of [[Caruso St John]], [[Stirling Prize]] winner\n*[[Alina Payne]] (BArch 1977) &ndash; professor of History of Art and Architecture at [[Harvard University]]\n*[[Amale Andraos]] (BArch 1996) &ndash; founder of New York-based architecture firm WORKac\n*Andre Vecsei (MArch 1973) &ndash; co-founder of Vecsei Architects with wife [[Eva Vecsei]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bluebeard.micro.org/about-the-author/|title=A cultured man who cheated death in Hungary|author=Alan Hustak|publisher=Montreal Gazette|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Anne Cormier (BArch 1982) &ndash; co-founder of Atelier Big City, 1998 [[Prix de Rome (Canada)|Prix de Rome]] winner<ref name=AtelierBigCity>{{cite web|url=https://www.atelierbigcity.com/team|title=Atelier Big City / Cormier, Cohen, Davies, architects|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Annie Lebel (BSc[Arch] 1989, BArch 1991) &ndash; co-founder of Atelier In Situ, 2001 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=Alumni2 />\n*[[Arthur Erickson]] (BArch 1950) &ndash; architect of [[Robson Square]], the [[Embassy of Canada in Washington, D.C.|Canadian Embassy]] and [[Roy Thompson Hall]]\n*[[Blanche Lemco van Ginkel|Blanche van Ginkel]] (BArch 1945) &ndash; first woman to head a faculty of architecture in Canada and be awarded a fellowship by the [[Royal Architectural Institute of Canada|RAIC]]<ref>Annmarie Adams, (2015). [http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/blanche-lemco-van-ginkel/ Article: Blanche Lemco van Ginkel], Canadian Encyclopedia. Accessed April 14, 2019.</ref>\n*[[Catherine Mary Wisnicki|Catherine Chard Wisnicki]] (B. Arch. 1943) &ndash; first female architecture graduate at McGill and one of the first female registered architects in Canada\n*[[Dimitri Dimakopoulos]] (BArch 1955) &ndash; of [[Affleck, Desbarats, Dimakopoulos, Lebensold, Sise]], designed [[Place Ville-Marie]]<ref name=\"Collectif2012\">{{cite book|last=Collectif|first=|title=Place Ville Marie: Montreal's Shining Landmark|date=21 September 2012|publisher=Qu\u00e9bec Amerique|language=English|isbn=9782764411728|page=207}}</ref> and [[1000 de La Gauchetiere]]\n*[[Dorice Constance Brown Walford|Dorice Walford]] (MArch 1958) &ndash; one of the first Canadian women in architecture to specialize in designing buildings for institutions\n*Eric Bunge (BSc[Arch] 1989, BArch 1991) &ndash; [[American Institute of Architects|FAIA]], co-founder of nARCHITECTS, 2005 Prix de Rome winner<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arch.columbia.edu/faculty/169-eric-bunge|title=Eric Bunge|publisher=Columbia GSAPP|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Frances Bronet]] (BSc[Arch] 1977, BArch 1978) &ndash; president of the [[Pratt Institute]] in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pratt.edu/the-institute/administration-resources/office-of-the-president/about/|title=Pratt Institute {{!}} The Institute {{!}} Administration and Resources {{!}} Office of the President {{!}} About Frances Bronet|website=www.pratt.edu|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n*[[Gavin Affleck]] (BArch 1985) &ndash; architect and son of [[Raymond Affleck|Ray Affleck]]\n*[[Gluskin Sheff|Gerald Sheff]] (BArch 1964) &ndash; founder of [[Gluskin Sheff + Associates Inc.]] and benefactor of the Gluskin Sheff Travel Scholarship at McGill\n*[[Gregory Henriquez]] (MArch 1988) &ndash; Vancouver-based architect<ref>{{cite web|url=https://henriquezpartners.com/teams/gregory-henriquez/|title=Gregory Henriquez|publisher=Henriquez Partners|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Arcop|Guy Desbarats]] (BArch 1948) &ndash; co-founder of Montreal-based architectural firm [[Arcop]]\n*Hal Ingberg (BSc[Arch] 1983, BArch 1985) &ndash; architect of [[Palais des congr\u00e8s de Montr\u00e9al]], 1993 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=Alumni2>{{cite web|url=https://mcgillnews.mcgill.ca/s/1762/news/interior.aspx?sid=1762&gid=2&pgid=551|title=City builders, McGill Alumni|author=Daniel McCabe|publisher=McGill News Alumni Magazine|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Harry Mayerovitch]] (BArch 1933) &ndash; architect, artist and cartoonist\n*Howard Davies (BSc[Arch] 1982, BArch 1983) &ndash; Professor of Practice at the School, co-founder of Atelier Big City, 1998 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=AtelierBigCity /><ref name=Faculty />\n*[[Janet Leys Shaw Mactavish]] (BArch 1947) &ndash; architect of the [[McIntyre Medical Sciences Building]] at McGill<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=i8oVMPqR3BIC&pg=PA75&lpg=PA75&dq=Janet+Leys+Shaw+Mactavish+mcgill&source=bl&ots=V7uLYkgbX_&sig=ACfU3U392NVXQ9W4TnXnNe4d9rbuMteJ-Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjX9szr0o7oAhX0oFwKHa8hDU4Q6AEwAnoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Janet%20Leys%20Shaw%20Mactavish%20mcgill&f=false|author=Annmarie Adams, Peta Tancred|title=Designing Women: Gender and the Architectural Profession, Heritage Series|page=75|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=2000|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[John Campbell Merrett]] (BArch 1931) &ndash; staff architect for [[Canadian National Railway]] and town planner of [[Pointe-Claire, Quebec]]\n*[[Karl Fischer (architect)|Karl Fischer]] (BSc[Arch] 1971, BArch 1972) &ndash; New York-based architect and benefactor of the Karl Fischer Scholarship at McGill\n*Katsuhiro Yamazaki (BSc[Arch] 1994, BArch 1996) &ndash; co-founder of Atelier TAG, 2007 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=Alumni2 />\n*[[Lucien Lagrange]] (BArch 1972) &ndash; former partner at [[Skidmore, Owings & Merrill]] and founder of [[Lucien Lagrange Architects|Lucien Lagrange & Associates]]\n*[[Ludger Lemieux]] &ndash; architect known for his Art Deco buildings in Montreal, notably [[Atwater Market]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/archives/379526/ludger-and-paul-m-lemieux-fonds|title=Ludger and Paul M. Lemieux fonds|publisher=Canadian Centre for Architecture|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Manon Asselin (BSc[Arch] 1990, BArch 1992, MArch 2001) &ndash; co-founder of Atelier TAG, 2007 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=Alumni2 />\n*[[Marc Mayer]] (B.A. 1984) &ndash; arts manager and curator\n*[[Maxwell M. Kalman]] (BArch 1931) &ndash; designed over 1,100 projects in Quebec, including Canada's first shopping centre\n*[[Melvin Charney]] (BArch 1958) &ndash; architect known for designing the [[sculpture garden]] at the [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]]\n*[[Moshe Safdie]] (MArch 1961) &ndash; architect of [[Habitat 67]], [[Marina Bay Sands]], [[Jewel Changi Airport]] and the [[Montreal Museum of Fine Arts]]\n*[[Peter Oberlander]] (BArch 1945) &ndash; architect and Canada's first professor of Urban and Regional Planning\n*Rami Bebawi (BSc[Arch] 1999, MArch 2001) &ndash; co-founder of [[KANVA Architecture]], 2017 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=Alumni2 /> \n*Randy Cohen (BSc[Arch] 1981, BArch 1982) &ndash; co-founder of Atelier Big City, 1998 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=AtelierBigCity />\n*[[Raymond Affleck]] (BArch 1947) &ndash; co-founder of [[Arcop]]\n*[[Raymond Moriyama]] (MArch 1957) &ndash; architect of [[Ottawa City Hall]], [[Bata Shoe Museum]] and [[Scarborough City Centre]]\n*[[WZMH Architects|Ren\u00e9 Menk\u00e8s]] (BArch 1955) &ndash; co-founder of [[WZMH Architects]], architect of [[CN Tower]]\n*[[Robert John Pratt]] (BArch 1933) &ndash; politician and architect\n*[[Robert Jolicoeur]], landscape architect and designer of [[International Federation for Equestrian Sports|FEI]] equestrian show jumping courses\n*[[Robert Libman]] (BArch 1985) &ndash; politician and architect\n*Robert Magne (BArch 1976) &ndash; architect of the [[Bell Centre]]<ref name=Alumni2 />\n*Robert Mellin (MArch 1984) &ndash; president of the [[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mcgill.ca/architecture/channels/news/prof-robert-mellin-elected-president-rca-268189|title=Prof. Robert Mellin elected President of RCA|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture, McGill University|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Robert Schofield Morris]] (BArch 1923) &ndash; architect and [[Royal Gold Medal|RIBA Gold Medal]] recipient<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionaryofarchitectsincanada.org/node/2338|title=Morris, Robert Schofield|publisher=Biographical Dictionary of Architects in Canada: 1800-1950|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n*St\u00e9phane Pratte (BSc[Arch] 1989, BArch 1991) &ndash; co-founder of Atelier In Situ, 2001 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=Alumni2 />\n*[[Ted Remerowski]] (BSc[Arch] 1970) &ndash; film producer\n*Tudor Radulescu (BSc[Arch] 1998, MArch 1991) &ndash; co-founder of [[KANVA Architecture]], 2017 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=Alumni2 />\n*[[Witold Rybczynski]] (BArch 1966, MArch 1972) &ndash; architectural writer/researcher\n<ref name=History /><ref name=Alumni />\n\n===Current and former faculty===\n*[[Alberto P\u00e9rez-G\u00f3mez]] &ndash; professor (current)<ref name=Faculty />\n*[[Annmarie Adams]] &ndash; associate professor (current) and former director of the School<ref name=Faculty />\n*[[Eva Vecsei|Andre Vecsei]] &ndash; visiting professor\n*[[Andrew Taylor (architect)|Andrew Taylor]] &ndash; taught freehand and model drawing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/taylor_andrew_thomas_16E.html|title=TAYLOR, Sir ANDREW THOMAS|publisher=University of Toronto/Universit\u00e9 Laval|website=Dictionary of Canadian Biography|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Arthur Lismer]] &ndash; member of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]], taught from 1941 to 1955<ref name=Lismer />\n*[[Dan Hanganu]] &ndash; architect of the [[Pointe-\u00e0-Calli\u00e8re Museum]] and the [[HEC Montr\u00e9al]] building\n*Douglas Shadbolt &ndash; director of architecture schools at [[Technical University of Nova Scotia]] (1961\u20131968), [[Carleton University]] (1968\u20131979) and [[University of British Columbia]] (1979\u20131990),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/article/douglas-shadbolt|title=Douglas Shadbolt|publisher=The Canadian Encyclopedia|author=Michael Mcmordie|date=2013|accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref> taught at McGill's School of Architecture from 1958 to 1961\n*[[Ernest Cormier]] &ndash; taught from 1919 to 1920<ref name=Cormier />\n*Frederic Lasserre &ndash; founder of the School of Architecture at the [[University of British Columbia]]\n*[[:fr:Fred Lebensold|Fred Lebensold]] &ndash; co-founder of [[Arcop]], taught from 1949 to 1955\n*[[Gavin Affleck]] &ndash; visiting professor\n*[[Gentile Tondino]] &ndash; renowned artist, taught from 1959 to 1999\n*[[Saucier + Perrotte#Founders|Gilles Saucier]] &ndash; founder of [[Saucier + Perrotte]], designed the [[Elizabeth Wirth Music Building]] on McGill campus, course lecturer (current)\n*[[Arcop|Guy Desbarats]] &ndash; co-founder of [[Arcop|Affleck, Desbarats, Dimakopoulos, Lebensold, Sise]]\n*[[Harold Lea Fetherstonhaugh]] &ndash; architect of many buildings on McGill's campus, including Douglas Hall and [[McGill University School of Religious Studies|William and Henry Birks Building]]\n*[[Hazen Sise]] &ndash; co-founder of [[Arcop|Affleck, Desbarats, Dimakopoulos, Lebensold, Sise]]\n*[[John Bland (architect)|John Bland]] &ndash; architect, served as director of the School for 31 years\n*[[John C. Parkin]] &ndash; co-founder of [[List of works by John B. Parkin Associates|John B. Parkin Associates]], visiting professor\n*Matthew Lella &ndash; principal at [[Diamond Schmitt Architects]], visiting professor\n*[[Michael Jemtrud]] &ndash; associate professor (current)<ref name=Faculty />\n*[[Moshe Safdie]] &ndash; visiting professor\n*[[Percy Nobbs]] &ndash; architect of many buildings on McGill's campus, including the [[Redpath Library]] and [[Osler Library]] buildings, taught from 1903 to 1939<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archivalcollections.library.mcgill.ca/index.php/percy-erskine-nobbs|title=Fonds 1 - Percy Erskine Nobbs Fonds|publisher=McGill Archival Collections Catalogue|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Peter Guo-hua Fu &ndash; Professor of Practice (current), eponym of the Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture\n*[[Peter Rose (architect)|Peter Rose]] &ndash; architect of [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-VZuLglXfrMC&pg=PA241&lpg=PA241&dq=Peter+Rose+mcgill&source=bl&ots=lrFArSFKLW&sig=ACfU3U3xmfYaMVZl6OicBeR2vwe95QW-xg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjosf_HzI7oAhXNT8AKHRRYBfQQ6AEwAXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=Peter%20Rose%20mcgill&f=false|author=Louise Pelletier, Alberto P\u00e9rez-G\u00f3mez|title=Architecture, Ethics, and Technology|page=241|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press - MQUP|year=1994|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Ramsay Traquair (architect)|Ramsay Traquair]] &ndash; third director of the School, taught from 1913 to 1939\n*[[Raymond Affleck|Ray Affleck]] &ndash; co-founder of [[Arcop]], visiting professor from 1967 to 1975<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/archives/225767/ray-affleck-fonds|title=Ray Affleck fonds|publisher=CCA|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Ricardo L. Castro]] &ndash; associate professor (current) since 1983<ref name=Faculty />\n*[[Stewart Henbest Capper]] &ndash; first director of the School, taught from 1896 to 1903\n*[[Warren Chalk]] &ndash; founding member of [[Archigram]], visiting professor\n<ref name=History /><ref name=Alumni /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/sheffprofessor#sheff2006|title=Gerald Sheff Visiting Professorship in Architecture|website=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|publisher=McGill University|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada}}\n* [[List of architecture schools#North America|List of architecture schools in Canada]]\n* [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]]\n* [[McCall MacBain Arts Building]]\n* [[Stephen Leacock Building]]\n* [[Elizabeth Wirth Music Building]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|McGill University}}\n{{Scholia|organization}}\n*[https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture Official Website]\n*[http://www.aias.org/ AIAS Official Website]\n\n{{McGill}}\n{{Navboxes\n|titlestyle = background:#CD202C; color:#ffffff; border:1px solid #000000;\n{{Montreal}}\n{{Qc Uni}}\n{{U15}}\n{{Association of American Universities}}\n{{Faith and Globalisation Network}}\n{{Universities Research Association}}\n{{Can-sem}}\n{{Universities in Canada |state=collapsed}}\n}}\n[[Category:McGill University]]\n[[Category:1896 establishments in Quebec]]\n[[Category:Architecture schools in Canada]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1896]]\n", "name_user": "Jonahrapp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBuildings and resources:created section Libraries and Collections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/McGill_School_of_Architecture"}
